# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-memory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-memory/advances-in-librarianship] The debut issue in 1970, edited by Melvin J.
[src:american-memory/advances-in-librarianship] Voight, was praised by Estelle Brodman from the *Bulletin of the Medical Library Association*, and also by Frederick Wezeman from *The Library Quarterly*, who called it "an auspicious beginning" to a journal which he hoped would continue.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The pilot for the American Memory project was a digitization program which started in 1990.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Selected Library of Congress holdings including examples of film, video, audio recordings, books and photographs were digitized and distributed on Laserdisc and CD-ROM.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] When the World Wide Web accelerated in 1993, the pilot program was refocused to deliver digitized materials by way of the internet.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The National Digital Library was created through bipartisan support in the United States Congress.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Initially publicly funded with $15 million over five years, a public-private partnership of entrepreneurs and philanthropists led to more than $45 million in private sponsorship from 1994 through 2000.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] At first, only $13 million was donated from private sectors but the project gained momentum as the years went on.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The competition produced 23 digital collections that complement American Memory, which now features more than 100 thematic collections.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The American Memory project started as a two-part effort of the National Digital Library Project (NDLP).
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Starting in 1994, the goal of the NDLP to digitize millions of items by the year 2000 would not only be met but would even go beyond that when the year finally came.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The first part or phase of the effort was piloted by the American Memory project which would have an extensive amount of the Library of Congress' source-materials digitized.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Another segment of the first phase possessed the goal of establishing a way or model to somehow share or distribute such source-materials between libraries.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Phase two of the project saw the continuation of the digitization of the materials from the Library of Congress but also other libraries as well.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The content included in the digital library through American Memory and the NDLP is vast and includes a wide array of historical items.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] Some items featured include, but is not limited to, the photographic collection on transportation, Henry Ford and the automobile, the sewing machine, and Robert J.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] As a result of the three-year competition and all the new individual projects making American Memory more readily available, American Memory started to become recognized on a larger scale.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] In 1996, *Time* magazine named American Memory one of the top ten best websites in the United States.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The website was also among the six finalists in the Education segment of the National Information Infrastructure Awards Program in 1996.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The project continued to receive citations and awards since it was established in 1990 and it has also helped serve on the research front from time to time.
[src:american-memory/american-memory] The National Digital Library exceeded its goal of making five million items available online by 2000.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech was created as a holding company that owned five former Bell System companies in the Midwest.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] For Ameritech's first nine years, it maintained these Bell brands inherited from the Bell System—though public displays of the Bell companies' names were often captioned "An Ameritech Company".
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] In January 1993, Ameritech officially retired the Bell brands and marketed itself with solely the Ameritech name across all five states in its territory.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] It added "d/b/a Ameritech (state)" to the names of its Bells to communicate brand unity.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech also owned Ameritech Cellular, a wireless company that operated cellular networks in many of the major cities of these states.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech Cellular was previously called Ameritech Mobile Communications.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech also provided cable television service in select areas as part of the Americast venture with other phone companies during the 1990s.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech Advanced Data Services (AADS) Network Access Point (NAP) was one of the original four National Science Foundation exchange points in the United States starting in 1994.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] AADS was a Tier 1 network Internet Exchange Point in Chicago, Illinois that provided service to higher education and research networks via a program called Star TAP and commercial networks.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] After the merger with SBC, AADS did business as the SBC Network Access Point or SBC/AADS NAP.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Prior to its merger with SBC Communications, Ameritech's corporate headquarters were in a leased space above the Chicago Mercantile Exchange on floors 34 through 39 of 30 S Wacker Dr, Chicago.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Further corporate offices were located at 225 W Randolph St, Chicago (formerly "The Illinois Bell Building") and 2000 W.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Ameritech Center Drive, Hoffman Estates) ("The Ameritech Center").
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] It was traded on the NYSE under the "AIT" symbol.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] In May 1998, Ameritech announced its intent to merge with SBC Communications for $62 billion.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] This brought great concern to Federal and state regulators, who in turn did not approve the merger until SBC and Ameritech agreed to several conditions to ensure adequate competition.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] On October 6, 1999, the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) approved the merger between SBC and Ameritech, then the two companies officially merged on October 8, 1999.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Prior to the merger, Ameritech's Chairman and CEO was Richard Notebaert, who later (in 2002) became CEO of competitor Qwest.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] On January 15, 2003, SBC Communications changed its d.b.a. names, changed the legal name of Ameritech Corp. to **SBC Teleholdings, Inc.**, which began doing business as **SBC Midwest**.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] On January 15, 2006, d.b.a names were again changed to align with SBC's assumption of the AT&T brand identity following its acquisition of AT&T Corp. the previous year, and Ameritech was again renamed, becoming **AT&T Teleholdings, Inc.** and began doing business as **AT&T Midwest**.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] Several Ameritech subsidiaries remain legally named "Ameritech", such as Ameritech Advanced Services; however, they do business as "AT&T Advanced Solutions".
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] In 2006, the holding companies Pacific Telesis and Southern New England Telecommunications were legally merged into AT&T Teleholdings.
[src:american-memory/ameritech-corporation] The company then became a holding company for Pacific Bell (and its subsidiary Nevada Bell) and Southern New England Telephone.
[src:american-memory/archive] An **archive** is an accumulation of historical records or materials, in any medium, or the physical facility in which they are located.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives contain primary source documents that have accumulated over the course of an individual or organization's lifetime, and are kept to show the history and function of that person or organization.
[src:american-memory/archive] Professional archivists and historians generally understand archives to be records that have been naturally and necessarily generated as a product of regular legal, commercial, administrative, or social activities.
[src:american-memory/archive] They have been metaphorically defined as "the secretions of an organism", and are distinguished from documents that have been consciously written or created to communicate a particular message to posterity.
[src:american-memory/archive] Generally, archives consist of records that have been selected for permanent or long-term preservation on the grounds of their enduring cultural, historical, or evidentiary value.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archival records are normally unpublished and very often unique, unlike books or magazines, of which many identical copies may exist.
[src:american-memory/archive] This means that archives are quite distinct from libraries with regard to their functions and organization, although archival collections can often be found within library buildings.
[src:american-memory/archive] While archives are traditionally collections of documents, some scholars argue that buildings can be a type of archive.
[src:american-memory/archive] The choice of what to include in an archive can be a political act.
[src:american-memory/archive] A person who works in archives is called an archivist.
[src:american-memory/archive] The study and practice of organizing, preserving, and providing access to information and materials in archives is called archival science.
[src:american-memory/archive] The physical place of storage can be referred to as an archive (more usual in the United Kingdom), an archives (more usual in the United States), or a repository.
[src:american-memory/archive] The use of the term "archive" with regards to computing (referring to a computer file storing the content of one or more others) should not be confused with the record-keeping meaning.
[src:american-memory/archive] The English word *archive* /ˈɑːrkaɪv/ is derived from the French *archives* (plural), and in turn from Latin *archīum* or *archīvum*, the romanized form of the Greek ἀρχεῖον (*arkheion*).
[src:american-memory/archive] The Greek term originally referred to the home or dwelling of the Archon, a ruler or chief magistrate, in which important official state documents were filed and interpreted; from there its meaning broadened to encompass such concepts as "town hall" and "public records".
[src:american-memory/archive] The root of the Greek word is ἀρχή (*arkhē*), meaning among other things "magistracy, office, government", and derived from the verb ἄρχω (*arkhō*), meaning "to begin, rule, govern" (also the root of English words such as "anarchy" and "monarchy").
[src:american-memory/archive] The word *archive* was first attested in English in the early 17th century, and the word *archivist* in the mid-18th century, although in these periods both terms were usually used only in reference to foreign institutions and personnel.
[src:american-memory/archive] Not until the late 19th century did they begin to be used widely in domestic contexts.
[src:american-memory/archive] The adjective formed from *archive* is *archival*.
[src:american-memory/archive] The practice of keeping official documents is very old.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archaeologists have discovered archives of hundreds (and sometimes thousands) of clay tablets dating back to the third and second millennia BC in sites like Ebla, Mari, Amarna, Hattusas, Ugarit, and Pylos.
[src:american-memory/archive] These discoveries have been fundamental to learning about ancient alphabets, languages, literature, and politics.
[src:american-memory/archive] Oral literature, such as Palestinian hikaye, can also have archival functions for communities.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives were well developed by the ancient Chinese, the ancient Greeks, and the ancient Romans (who called them *Tabularia*).
[src:american-memory/archive] The idea that a society would designate a place to preserve records is integral to the Justinian Code (which set Roman law).
[src:american-memory/archive] England, after 1066, developed archives and archival access methods.
[src:american-memory/archive] The Swiss developed archival systems after 1450.
[src:american-memory/archive] The first predecessors of archival science in the West are Jacob von Rammingen's manuals of 1571. and Baldassarre Bonifacio's *De Archivis libris singularis* of 1632.
[src:american-memory/archive] Modern archiving has some roots dating back to the French Revolution.
[src:american-memory/archive] The French National Archives, which possess perhaps the largest archival collection in the world (with records going as far back as 625 A.D.), was created in 1790 during the Revolution from various government, religious, and private archives seized by the revolutionaries.
[src:american-memory/archive] Historians, genealogists, lawyers, demographers, filmmakers, and others conduct research at archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] The research process at each archive is unique and depends upon the institution that houses the archive.
[src:american-memory/archive] While there are many kinds of archives, the most recent census of archivists in the United States identifies five major types: **academic**, **business (for profit)**, **government**, **non-profit**, and **others**.
[src:american-memory/archive] There are also four main areas of inquiry involved with archives: material technologies, organizing principles, geographic locations, and tangled embodiments of humans and non-humans.
[src:american-memory/archive] These areas help to further categorize what kind of archive is being created.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives in colleges, universities, and other educational facilities are typically housed within a library, and duties may be carried out by an archivist.
[src:american-memory/archive] Academic archives exist to preserve institutional history and serve the academic community.
[src:american-memory/archive] Access to the collections in these archives is usually by prior appointment only; some have posted hours for making inquiries.
[src:american-memory/archive] Users of academic archives can be undergraduates, graduate students, faculty and staff, scholarly researchers, and the general public.
[src:american-memory/archive] Many academic archives work closely with alumni relations departments or other campus institutions to help raise funds for their library or school.
[src:american-memory/archive] Entry-level positions usually require an undergraduate diploma, but typically archivists hold graduate degrees in history or library science (preferably certified by a body such as the American Library Association).
[src:american-memory/archive] Subject-area specialization becomes more common in higher-ranking positions.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives located in for-profit institutions are usually those owned by a private business.
[src:american-memory/archive] Examples of prominent business archives in the United States include Coca-Cola (which also owns the separate museum World of Coca-Cola), Procter and Gamble, Motorola Heritage Services and Archives, and Levi Strauss & Co.
[src:american-memory/archive] These corporate archives maintain historic documents and items related to the history and administration of their companies.
[src:american-memory/archive] Business archives serve the purpose of helping corporations maintain control over their brand by retaining memories of the company's past.
[src:american-memory/archive] Especially in business archives, records management is separate from the historical aspect of archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] Workers in these types of archives may have any combination of training and degrees, from either a history or library background.
[src:american-memory/archive] These archives are typically not open to the public and are only used by workers of the owner company, though some allow approved visitors by appointment.
[src:american-memory/archive] Business archives are concerned with maintaining the integrity of their company and are therefore selective about how their materials may be used.
[src:american-memory/archive] Government archives include those maintained by local and state governments as well as those maintained by the national (or federal) government.
[src:american-memory/archive] Anyone may use a government archive, and frequent users include reporters, genealogists, writers, historians, students, and people seeking information on the history of their home or region.
[src:american-memory/archive] Many government archives are open to the public, and no appointment is required to visit.
[src:american-memory/archive] In the United States, the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA) maintains central archival facilities in the District of Columbia and College Park, Maryland, with regional facilities distributed throughout the United States.
[src:american-memory/archive] Some city or local governments may have repositories, but their organization and accessibility vary widely.
[src:american-memory/archive] Similar to the library profession, certification requirements and education also varies widely, from state to state.
[src:american-memory/archive] Professional associations themselves encourage the need to professionalize.
[src:american-memory/archive] NARA offers the Certificate of Federal Records Management Training Program for professional development.
[src:american-memory/archive] The majority of state and local archives staff hold a bachelor's degree—increasingly repositories list advanced degrees (e.g.
[src:american-memory/archive] MA, MLS/MLIS, Ph.D.) and certifications as a position requirement or preference.
[src:american-memory/archive] In the UK, the National Archives (formerly known as the Public Record Office) is the government archive for England and Wales.
[src:american-memory/archive] The physical records stored by the National Archives amount to 185 km (115 miles) of shelving, a number that increases every year.
[src:american-memory/archive] The English Heritage Archive is the public archive of English Heritage.
[src:american-memory/archive] The National Records of Scotland, located in Edinburgh, serves that country; while the Public Record Office of Northern Ireland in Belfast is the government archive for Northern Ireland.
[src:american-memory/archive] A network of county record offices and other local authority-run archives exists throughout England, Wales, and Scotland and holds many important collections, including local government, landed estates, church, and business records.
[src:american-memory/archive] Many archives have contributed catalogs to the national "Access to Archives" program and online searching across collections is possible.
[src:american-memory/archive] Put together, the total volume of archives under the supervision of the French Archives Administration is the largest in the world.
[src:american-memory/archive] The archives of the French Ministry of Armed Forces (Defence Historical Service, ca.
[src:american-memory/archive] 450 kilometres (280 mi) of physical records) and the archives of the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Diplomatic Archives , ca.
[src:american-memory/archive] 120 kilometres (75 mi) of physical records) are managed separately by their respective ministries and do not fall under the jurisdiction of the Archives of France Administration.
[src:american-memory/archive] In India, the National Archives (NAI) are located in New Delhi.
[src:american-memory/archive] In Taiwan, the National Archives Administration are located in Taipei.
[src:american-memory/archive] Most intergovernmental organizations keep their own historical archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] However, a number of European organizations, including the European Commission, choose to deposit their archives with the European University Institute in Florence.
[src:american-memory/archive] A prominent church archive is the Vatican Apostolic Archive.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archdioceses, dioceses, and parishes also have archives in the Roman Catholic and Anglican Churches.
[src:american-memory/archive] Very important are monastery archives because of their antiquity, like the ones of Monte Cassino, Saint Gall, and Fulda.
[src:american-memory/archive] The records in these archives include manuscripts, papal records, local church records, photographs, oral histories, audiovisual materials, and architectural drawings.
[src:american-memory/archive] Film archives collect, restore, investigate and conserve audiovisual content like films, documentaries, tv programs and newsreel footage.
[src:american-memory/archive] Often, a country has its own film archive to preserve its national audiovisual heritage.
[src:american-memory/archive] The International Federation of Film Archives comprises more than 150 institutions in over 77 countries and the Association of European Film Archives and Cinematheques is an affiliation of 49 European national and regional film archives founded in 1991.
[src:american-memory/archive] Non-profit archives include those in historical societies, not-for-profit businesses such as hospitals, and repositories within foundations.
[src:american-memory/archive] Such repositories are typically set up with private funds from donors to preserve the papers and histories of specific people or places.
[src:american-memory/archive] These institutions may rely on grant funding from the government as well as private funds.
[src:american-memory/archive] Depending on the availability of funds, non-profit archives may be as small as the historical society in a rural town to as big as a state historical society that rivals a government archive.
[src:american-memory/archive] Users of this type of archive may vary as much as the institutions that hold it.
[src:american-memory/archive] Employees of non-profit archives may be professional archivists, paraprofessionals, or volunteers, as the education required for a position at a non-profit archive varies with the demands of the collection's user base.
[src:american-memory/archive] Web archiving is the process of collecting portions of the World Wide Web and ensuring the collection is preserved in an archive, such as an archive site, for future researchers, historians, and the public.
[src:american-memory/archive] Due to the massive size of the Web, web archivists typically employ web crawlers for automated collection.
[src:american-memory/archive] Similarly, software code and documentation can be archived on the web, as with the example of CPAN.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives that are collected and kept in cold storage (i.e., not openly accessible) are sometimes called *dark archives*.
[src:american-memory/archive] For example in 2025, the academic paper repository arXiv was concerned about trends in the United States and elsewhere that might restrict academic freedoms.
[src:american-memory/archive] They created a dark archive of the website, so it could be reconstituted in another country, if required.
[src:american-memory/archive] *Dark archive* is also used in library science for collections of online publications that are held in reserve in case the publisher no longer makes them available.
[src:american-memory/archive] There are tribal archives within the Native American nations in North America, and there are archives that exist within the papers of private individuals.
[src:american-memory/archive] Many museums keep archives in order to prove the provenance of their pieces.
[src:american-memory/archive] Any institution or persons wishing to keep their significant papers in an organized fashion that employs the most basic principles of archival science may have an archive.
[src:american-memory/archive] In the 2004 census of archivists taken in the United States, 2.7% of archivists were employed in institutions that defied categorization.
[src:american-memory/archive] This was a separate figure from the 1.3% that identified themselves as self-employed.
[src:american-memory/archive] Another type of archive is the Public Secrets project.
[src:american-memory/archive] This is an interactive testimonial, in which women incarcerated in the California State Prison System describe what happened to them.
[src:american-memory/archive] The archive's mission is to gather stories from women who want to express themselves and want their stories heard.
[src:american-memory/archive] This collection includes transcripts and an audio recording of the women telling their stories.
[src:american-memory/archive] The archives of an individual may include letters, papers, photographs, computer files, scrapbooks, financial records, or diaries created or collected by the individual, regardless of medium or format.
[src:american-memory/archive] The archives of an organization (such as a corporation or government) tend to contain other types of records, such as administrative files, business records, memos, official correspondence, and meeting minutes.
[src:american-memory/archive] Some archives are made up of a compilation of both types of collections.
[src:american-memory/archive] An example of this type of combined compilation is the Transgender Archives at the University of Victoria, which contain a multitude of collections of donations from both individuals and organizations from all over the world.
[src:american-memory/archive] Many of these donations have yet to be cataloged but are currently in the process of being digitally preserved and made available to the public online.
[src:american-memory/archive] The Arctic World Archive is a commercially-run facility for data preservation located in the Svalbard archipelago, Norway, that contains data of historical and cultural interest from several countries as well as all of American multinational company GitHub's open source code.
[src:american-memory/archive] The data is kept on reels of specially developed film in a steel vault buried deep beneath the permafrost, with the data storage medium expected to last for 500 to 1000 years.
[src:american-memory/archive] The International Council on Archives (ICA) has developed a number of standards on archival description, including the General International Standard Archival Description ISAD(G).
[src:american-memory/archive] ISAD (G) is meant to be used in conjunction with national standards or as a basis for nations to build their own standards.
[src:american-memory/archive] In the United States, ISAD (G) is implemented through Describing Archives: A Content Standard, popularly known as "DACS".
[src:american-memory/archive] In Canada, ISAD (G) is implemented through the Council of Archives as the Rules for Archival Description, also known as "RAD".
[src:american-memory/archive] The cultural property stored in archives is threatened by natural disasters, wars, or other emergencies in many countries.
[src:american-memory/archive] International partners for archives are UNESCO and Blue Shield International, in accordance with the Hague Convention for the Protection of Cultural Property from 1954 and its 2nd Protocol from 1999.
[src:american-memory/archive] From a national and international perspective, there are many collaborations between archives and local Blue Shield organizations to ensure the sustainable existence of cultural property storage facilities.
[src:american-memory/archive] In addition to working with United Nations peacekeeping in the event of war, the protection of the archives requires the creation of "no-strike lists", the linking of civil and military structures, and the training of local personnel.
[src:american-memory/archive] Archives that primarily contain physical artifacts and printed documents are increasingly shifting to digitizing items that did not originate digitally, which are then usually stored away.
[src:american-memory/archive] Both physical and digital archives also generally have specific limitations regarding the types of content that are deemed able to be preserved, categorized, and archived.
[src:american-memory/archive] Conventional institutionalized archive spaces have a tendency to prioritize tangible items over ephemeral experiences, actions, effects, and even bodies.
[src:american-memory/archive] As Omnia El Shakry shows, dealing with destruction is a challenge central to decolonial historiography.
[src:american-memory/archive] When faced with a lack of archival documents, historians resort to different sources and methods.
[src:american-memory/archive] For example, due to the lack of a Palestinian state archive, many historians of Nakba had to rely on sources in the Israeli state's archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] Page's description of disseminating transgender history directly to trans people through various social media and networking platforms like tumblr, Twitter, and Instagram, as well as via podcast.
[src:american-memory/archive] While the majority of archived materials are typically well conserved within their collections, anarchiving's attention to ephemerality also brings to light the inherent impermanence and gradual change of physical objects over time as a result of being handled.
[src:american-memory/archive] The concept of counter-archiving brings into question what tends to be considered archivable and what is therefore selected to be preserved within conventional contemporary archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] With the options available through counter-archiving, there is the potential to "challenge traditional conceptions of history" as they are perceived within contemporary archives, which creates space for narratives that are often not present in many archival materials.
[src:american-memory/archive] The unconventional nature of counter-archiving practices makes room for the maintenance of ephemeral qualities contained within certain historically significant experiences, performances, and personally or culturally relevant stories that do not typically have a space in conventional archives.
[src:american-memory/archive] The practices of anarchiving and counter-archiving are both rooted in social justice work.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A **CD-ROM** (/ˌsiːdiːˈrɒm/, **compact disc read-only memory**) is a type of read-only memory consisting of a pre-pressed optical compact disc that contains data computers can read, but not write or erase.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Some CDs, called enhanced CDs, hold both computer data and audio with the latter capable of being played on a CD player, while data (such as software or digital video) is only usable on a computer (such as ISO 9660 format PC CD-ROMs).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] During the 1990s and early 2000s, CD-ROMs were popularly used to distribute software and data for computers and fifth generation video game consoles.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] DVDs as well as downloading started to replace CD-ROMs in these roles starting in the early 2000s, and the use of CD-ROMs for commercial software is now rare.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The earliest theoretical work on optical disc storage was done by independent researchers in the United States including David Paul Gregg (1958) and James Russel (1965–1975).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In particular, Gregg's patents were used as the basis of the LaserDisc specification that was co-developed between MCA and Philips after MCA purchased Gregg's patents, as well as the company he founded, Gauss Electrophysics.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The LaserDisc was the immediate precursor to the CD, with the primary difference being that the LaserDisc encoded information through an analog process whereas the CD used digital encoding.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Key work to digitize the optical disc was performed by Toshi Doi and Kees Schouhamer Immink during 1979–1980, who worked on a taskforce for Sony and Philips.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The result was the Compact Disc Digital Audio (CD-DA), defined in 1980.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The CD-ROM was later designed as an extension of the CD-DA, and adapted this format to hold any form of digital data, with an initial storage capacity of 553 MB.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Sony and Philips created the technical standard that defines the format of a CD-ROM in 1983, in what came to be called the *Yellow Book*.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The CD-ROM was announced in 1984 and introduced by Denon and Sony at the first Japanese COMDEX computer show in 1985.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The first CD-ROM drive released to the public, the CM 100, was introduced in July 1985 by Philips.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In November 1985, several computer industry participants, including Microsoft, Philips, Sony, Apple and Digital Equipment Corporation, met to create a specification to define a file system format for CD-ROMs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The resulting specification, called the High Sierra format, was published in May 1986.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] It was eventually standardized, with a few changes, as the ISO 9660 standard in 1988.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] One of the first products to be made available to the public on CD-ROM was the *Grolier Academic Encyclopedia*, presented at the Microsoft CD-ROM Conference in March 1986.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROMs began being used in home video game consoles starting with the PC Engine CD-ROM2 (TurboGrafx-CD) in 1988, while CD-ROM drives had also become available for home computers by the end of the 1980s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In 1990, Data East demonstrated an arcade system board that supported CD-ROMs, similar to 1980s LaserDisc video games but with digital data, allowing more flexibility than older LaserDisc games.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] By early 1990, about 300,000 CD-ROM drives were sold in Japan, while 125,000 CD-ROM discs were being produced monthly in the United States.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Some computers that were marketed in the 1990s were called "multimedia" computers because they incorporated a CD-ROM drive, which allowed for the delivery of several hundred megabytes of video, picture, and audio data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The first laptop to have an integrated CD-ROM drive as an option was 1993's CF-V21P by Panasonic; however, the drive only supported mini CDs up to 3.5 inches in diameter.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The first notebook to support standard 4.7-inch-diameter discs was IBM's ThinkPad 755CD in 1994.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] On early audio CD players that were released prior to the advent of the CD-ROM, the raw binary data of CD-ROM was played back as noise.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] To address this problem, the subcode channel Q has a "data" flag in areas of the disc that contain computer data rather than playable audio.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The data flag instructs CD players to mute the audio.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROMs are identical in appearance to audio CDs, and data are stored and retrieved in a very similar manner (only differing from audio CDs in the standards used to store the data).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Discs are made from a 1.2 mm thick disc of polycarbonate plastic, with a thin layer of aluminium to make a reflective surface.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The most common size of CD-ROM is 120 mm in diameter, though the smaller Mini CD standard with an 80 mm diameter, as well as shaped compact discs in numerous non-standard sizes and molds (e.g., business card-sized media), also exist.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Data is stored on the disc as a series of microscopic indentations called "pits", with the non-indented spaces between them called "lands".
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A laser is shone onto the reflective surface of the disc to read the pattern of pits and lands.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Because the depth of the pits is approximately one-quarter to one-sixth of the wavelength of the laser light used to read the disc, the reflected beam's phase is shifted in relation to the incoming beam, causing destructive interference and reducing the reflected beam's intensity.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Several formats are used for data stored on compact discs, known as the Rainbow Books.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The *Yellow Book*, created in 1983, defines the specifications for CD-ROMs, standardized in 1988 as the ISO/IEC 10149 standard and in 1989 as the ECMA-130 standard.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The CD-ROM standard builds on top of the original *Red Book* CD-DA standard for CD audio.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Other standards, such as the *White Book* for Video CDs, further define formats based on the CD-ROM specifications.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The *Yellow Book* itself is not freely available, but the standards with the corresponding content can be downloaded for free from ISO or ECMA.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] There are several standards that define how to structure data files on a CD-ROM.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] ISO 9660 defines the standard file system for a CD-ROM.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] ISO 13490 is an improvement on this standard which adds support for non-sequential write-once and re-writeable discs such as CD-R and CD-RW, as well as multiple sessions.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The ISO 13346 standard was designed to address most of the shortcomings of ISO 9660, and a subset of it evolved into the UDF format, which was adopted for DVDs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A bootable CD specification, called El Torito, was issued in January 1995, to make a CD emulate a hard disk or floppy disk.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Pre-pressed CD-ROMs are mass-produced by a process of stamping where a glass master disc is created and used to make "stampers", which are in turn used to manufacture multiple copies of the final disc with the pits already present.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Recordable (CD-R) and rewritable (CD-RW) discs are manufactured by a different method, whereby the data are recorded on them by a laser changing the properties of a dye or phase transition material in a process that is often referred to as "burning".
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Data stored on CD-ROMs follows the standard CD data encoding techniques described in the *Red Book* specification (originally defined for audio CD only).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This includes cross-interleaved Reed–Solomon coding (CIRC), eight-to-fourteen modulation (EFM), and the use of pits and lands for coding the bits into the physical surface of the CD.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The structures used to group data on a CD-ROM are also derived from the *Red Book*.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Like audio CDs (CD-DA), a CD-ROM *sector* contains 2,352 bytes of user data, composed of 98 frames, each consisting of 33 bytes (24 bytes for the user data, 8 bytes for error correction, and 1 byte for the sub code).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Unlike audio CDs, the data stored in these sectors corresponds to any type of digital data, not audio samples encoded according to the audio CD specification.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] To structure, address and protect this data, the CD-ROM standard further defines two sector modes, Mode 1 and Mode 2, which describe two different layouts for the data inside a sector.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A track (a group of sectors) inside a CD-ROM only contains sectors in the same mode, but if multiple tracks are present in a CD-ROM, each track can have its sectors in a different mode from the rest of the tracks.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] They can also coexist with audio CD tracks, which is the case of mixed mode CDs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Both Mode 1 and 2 sectors use the first 16 bytes for header information, but differ in the remaining 2,336 bytes due to the use of error correction bytes.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Unlike an audio CD, a CD-ROM cannot rely on error concealment by interpolation; a higher reliability of the retrieved data is required.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] To achieve improved error correction and detection, Mode 1, used mostly for digital data, adds a 32-bit cyclic redundancy check (CRC) code for error detection, and a third layer of Reed–Solomon error correction using a Reed-Solomon Product-like Code (RSPC).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Mode 1 therefore contains 288 bytes per sector for error detection and correction, leaving 2,048 bytes per sector available for data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Mode 2, which is more appropriate for image or video data (where perfect reliability may be a little bit less important), contains no additional error detection or correction bytes, having therefore 2,336 available data bytes per sector.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Both modes, like audio CDs, still benefit from the lower layers of error correction at the frame level.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Before being stored on a disc with the techniques described above, each CD-ROM sector is scrambled to prevent some problematic patterns from showing up.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] These scrambled sectors then follow the same encoding process described in the *Red Book* in order to be finally stored on a CD.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The net byte rate of a Mode-1 CD-ROM, based on comparison to CD-DA audio standards, is 44,100 Hz × 16 bits/sample × 2 channels × 2,048 / 2,352 / 8 = 150 KiB/s (150 × 210) .
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This value, 150 KiB/s, is defined as "1× speed".
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Therefore, for Mode 1 CD-ROMs, a 1× CD-ROM drive reads 150/2 = 75 consecutive sectors per second.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The playing time of a standard CD is 74 minutes, or 4,440 seconds, contained in 333,000 blocks or sectors.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Therefore, the net capacity of a Mode-1 CD-ROM is 650 MiB (650 × 220).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] For 80 minute CDs, the capacity is 703 MiB.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROM XA defines two new sector layouts, called Mode 2 Form 1 and Mode 2 Form 2 (which are different from the original Mode 2).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] XA Mode 2 Form 1 is similar to the Mode 1 structure described above, and can interleave with XA Mode 2 Form 2 sectors; it is used for data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] XA Mode 2 Form 2 has 2,324 bytes of user data, and is similar to the standard Mode 2 but with error detection bytes added (though no error correction).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] It can interleave with XA Mode 2 Form 1 sectors, and it is used for audio/video data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Video CDs, Super Video CDs, Photo CDs, Enhanced Music CDs and CD-i use these sector modes.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] When a disc image of a CD-ROM is created, this can be done in either "raw" mode (extracting 2,352 bytes per sector, independent of the internal structure), or obtaining only the sector's useful data (2,048/2,336/2,352/2,324 bytes depending on the CD-ROM mode).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The file size of a disc image created in raw mode is *always* a multiple of 2,352 bytes (the size of a block).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Disc image formats that store raw CD-ROM sectors include CCD/IMG, CUE/BIN, and MDS/MDF.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The size of a disc image created from the data in the sectors will depend on the type of sectors it is using.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] For example, if a CD-ROM mode 1 image is created by extracting only each sector's data, its size will be a multiple of 2,048; this is usually the case for ISO disc images.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This is the upper limit for raw images created on a 74 min or ≈650 MB *Red Book* CD.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The 14.8% increase is due to the discarding of error correction data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROM capacities are normally expressed with binary prefixes, subtracting the space used for error correction data.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The capacity of a CD-ROM depends on how close the outward data track is extended to the disc's outer rim.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A standard 120 mm, *700 MB* CD-ROM can actually hold about 703 MB of data with error correction (or 847 MB total).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In comparison, a single-layer DVD-ROM can hold 4.7 GB (4.7 × 109 bytes) of error-protected data, more than 6 CD-ROMs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROM discs are read using CD-ROM drives.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A CD-ROM drive may be connected to the computer via a PATA, SCSI, SATA, FireWire, or USB interface or a proprietary interface, such as the Panasonic CD interface, LMSI/Philips, Sony and Mitsumi standards.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Virtually all modern CD-ROM drives can also play audio CDs (as well as Video CDs and other data standards) when used with the right software.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROM drives employ a near-infrared 780 nm laser diode.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The laser beam is directed onto the disc via an opto-electronic tracking module, which then detects whether the beam has been reflected or scattered.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-ROM drives are rated with a speed factor relative to music CDs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] If a Mode 1 CD-ROM is read at the same rotational speed as an audio CD, the data transfer rate is 150 Kbyte/s, commonly called "1×" (with constant linear velocity, short *"CLV"*).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] At this data rate, the track moves along under the laser spot at about 1.2 m/s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] To maintain this linear velocity as the optical head moves to different positions, the angular velocity is varied from about 500 rpm at the inner edge to 200 rpm at the outer edge.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The 1× speed rating for CD-ROM (150 Kbyte/s) is different from the 1× speed rating for DVDs (1.32 MB/s).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] When the speed at which the disc is spun is increased, data can be transferred at greater rates.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] For example, a CD-ROM drive that can read at 8× speed spins the disc at 1600 to 4000 rpm, giving a linear velocity of 9.6 m/s and a transfer rate of 1200 Kbyte/s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Above 12× speed most drives read at Constant angular velocity (CAV, constant rpm) so that the motor is not made to change from one speed to another as the head seeks from place to place on the disc.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In CAV mode the "×" number denotes the transfer rate at the outer edge of the disc, where it is a maximum.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] 20× was thought to be the maximum speed due to mechanical constraints until Samsung Electronics introduced the SCR-3230, a 32× CD-ROM drive which uses a ball bearing system to balance the spinning disc in the drive to reduce vibration and noise.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] As of 2004, the fastest transfer rate commonly available was about 52× or 10,400 rpm and 7.62 MB/s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Higher spin speeds are limited by the strength of the polycarbonate plastic of which the discs are made.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] At 52×, the linear velocity of the outermost part of the disc is around 65 m/s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] However, improvements can still be obtained using multiple laser pickups as demonstrated by the Kenwood TrueX 72× which uses seven laser beams and a rotation speed of approximately 10×.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The first 12× drive was released in late 1996.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Above 12× speed, there are problems with vibration and heat.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CAV drives give speeds up to 30× at the outer edge of the disc with the same rotational speed as a standard (constant linear velocity, CLV) 12×, or 32× with a slight increase.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] However, due to the nature of CAV (linear speed at the inner edge is still only 12×, increasing smoothly in-between) the actual throughput increase is less than 30/12; in fact, roughly 20× average for a completely full disc, and even less for a partially filled one.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Problems with vibration, owing to limits on achievable symmetry and strength in mass-produced media, mean that CD-ROM drive speeds have not massively increased since the late 1990s.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Over 10 years later, commonly available drives vary between 24× (slimline and portable units, 10× spin speed) and 52× (typically CD- and read-only units, 21× spin speed), all using CAV to achieve their claimed "max" speeds, with 32× through 48× most common.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Even so, these speeds can cause poor reading (drive error correction having become very sophisticated in response) and even shattering of poorly made or physically damaged media, with small cracks rapidly growing into catastrophic breakages when centripetally stressed at 10,000–13,000 rpm (i.e.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] High rotational speeds also produce undesirable noise from disc vibration, rushing air and the spindle motor itself.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Most 21st-century drives allow forced low speed modes (by use of small utility programs) for the sake of safety, accurate reading or silence, and will automatically fall back if numerous sequential read errors and retries are encountered.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A similar stratification effect has since been seen in DVD development where maximum speed has stabilised at 16× CAV (with exceptional cases between 18× and 22×) and capacity at 4.3 and 8.5 GB (single and dual layer), with higher speed and capacity needs instead being catered to by Blu-ray drives.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] CD-Recordable drives are often sold with three different speed ratings: one speed for write-once operations, one for re-write operations, and one for read-only operations.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The speeds are typically listed in that order; i.e. a 12×/10×/32× CD drive can write to CD-R discs at 12× speed (1.76 MB/s), write to CD-RW discs at 10× speed (1.46 MB/s), and read from CDs at 32× speed (4.69 MB/s), if the CPU and media player software permit speeds that high.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] A 2003 MythBusters episode erroneously claims that a CD spinning at "52× speed" spins at 30,000 rotations per minute (rpm).
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This miscalculation is caused by assuming a **linear** velocity of 52× at the inner edge of the data area of the disc, which would indeed reach dangerous speeds of over 25,000 rpm, therefore optical drives never spin discs at such speeds.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] In actuality, a speed of "52×" are approximately 10,000 rpm, given that drives are advertised with their **angular** velocities.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] The angular velocity is the measured as the linear velocity at the outermost edge of the disc, where the linear velocity (and accordingly the data transfer rate) is roughly 2.5 times higher than at the innermost edge of the data area.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Software distributors, and in particular distributors of computer games, often make use of various copy protection schemes to prevent software running from any media besides the original CD-ROMs.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This differs somewhat from audio CD protection in that it is usually implemented in both the media and the software itself.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] Manufacturers of CD writers (CD-R or CD-RW) are encouraged by the music industry to ensure that every drive they produce has a unique identifier, which will be encoded by the drive on every disc that it records: the RID or Recorder Identification Code.
[src:american-memory/cd-rom] This is a counterpart to the Source Identification Code (SID), an eight character code beginning with "IFPI" that is usually stamped on discs produced by CD recording plants.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many titles featured CD-quality digital audio, and LaserDisc was the first home video format to support surround sound.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Its 425 to 440 horizontal lines of resolution was nearly double that of competing consumer videotape formats, VHS and Betamax, and approaching the resolution later achieved by DVDs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Despite these advantages, the format failed to achieve widespread adoption in North America or Europe, primarily due to the high cost of players and their inability to record.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In contrast, LaserDisc was significantly more popular in Japan and in wealthier regions of Southeast Asia, including Singapore and Malaysia, and it became the dominant rental video format in Hong Kong during the 1990s.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Its superior audiovisual quality made it a favorite among videophiles and film enthusiasts throughout its lifespan.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The technologies and concepts developed for LaserDisc laid the groundwork for subsequent optical media formats, including the compact disc (CD) and DVD.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc player production ended in July 2009 with Pioneer's exit from the market.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The origins of optical recording date back to 1963, when David Paul Gregg and James Russell developed a transparent disc-based system, later patented in 1970.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] MCA acquired the rights to this technology in 1968.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Separately, by 1969, Philips had developed a videodisc using reflective technology, which offered advantages over the transparent method.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] MCA and Philips began collaborating in the early 1970s and publicly demonstrated the videodisc format in 1972.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Internally, the technology was known by several names, including Optical Videodisc System, Reflective Optical Videodisc, Laser Optical Videodisc, and Video Long Play.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The format was commercially introduced as MCA DiscoVision on December 11, 1978, in a test market launch in Atlanta, Georgia, two years after the debut of VHS and four years before the introduction of the CD, which is based on laser disc technology.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The first LaserDisc title released in North America was the MCA DiscoVision edition of *Jaws* on December 15, 1978.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Philips produced the players, while MCA manufactured the discs; however, the partnership ultimately proved unsuccessful and was dissolved after several years.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In 1980, Pioneer acquired a majority stake in the format and began marketing it as both LaserVision (as the format name) and LaserDisc (as the brand).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some releases informally referred to it as Laser Videodisc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer's LaserDisc players debuted in Japan in October 1981.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By 1984, Philips and Sony had introduced LV-ROM, a version of the format designed to store digital data, offering a capacity of 3.28 GB, foreshadowing the capabilities of later formats such as CD-ROM or DVD-ROM.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Although LaserDisc never achieved mass-market success, the format gained modest popularity in select markets and developed a niche following.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In Japan, market penetration reached approximately 10% of households by 1999.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In the United States, about 2% of households (roughly two million) owned a player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] As of 2021, LaserDisc retains a small collector community in the United States and Japan.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In Europe, the format remained obscure, though it saw limited institutional use.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Notably, the British Broadcasting Corporation (BBC) employed LaserDisc for the BBC Domesday Project in the mid-1980s, and from the early 1990s through the late 1990s, also used Sony's CRVdisc variant to broadcast television idents.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc was largely supplanted by the DVD format by the early 2000s.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The last LaserDisc title released in North America was Paramount's *Bringing Out the Dead* on October 3, 2000.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In Japan, new titles continued to be released until September 21, 2001, with the final film being the Hong Kong action movie *Tokyo Raiders* from Golden Harvest.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The last known LaserDisc release of any kind was *Onta Station vol.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] 1018*, a karaoke title issued exclusively in Japan on March 21, 2007.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer ceased production of LaserDisc players in July 2009.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The company continued to offer maintenance services until September 30, 2020, when the remaining parts inventory was exhausted.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A total of 16.8 million LaserDisc players were sold worldwide, including 9.5 million units sold by Pioneer.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A standard LaserDisc used for home video was 300 millimeters (11.8 in) in diameter, roughly the same size as a 12-inch (305 mm) phonograph record.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] At a basic level, LaserDiscs used a series of tiny pits and flat areas (called lands) etched into the disc surface.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] These core technologies would later be reused in CDs and DVDs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] As a result, all three formats appear similar in physical design.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] However, LaserDisc differed significantly in how it stored information.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDiscs stored analog video using a composite signal format, offering picture quality comparable to the 1-inch (25 mm) Type C videotape format, with approximately 425 to 440 horizontal lines of resolution.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A carrier frequency was modulated by the video signal, and this signal was physically represented by the pattern of pits and lands on the disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] During playback, a laser read these patterns, enabling the player's circuitry to reconstruct the original analog signal.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Audio was originally recorded as analog stereo using frequency modulation.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Later discs introduced digital audio using pulse-code modulation (PCM), and by the 1990s, some titles supported digital surround sound formats such as Dolby Digital and DTS.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] These digital tracks were typically output through optical (TOSLINK) or coaxial (S/PDIF) connections to an external digital-to-analog converter.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Digital PCM audio was encoded by directly summing its baseband signal with the FM-modulated video and analog audio carriers.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This combined signal was then clipped, creating a square wave whose transitions are recorded as the pattern of pits and lands on the disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The frequency of these transitions represented the high-frequency video information.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Meanwhile, the lower-frequency digital and analog audio signals caused variations in the signal's duty cycle, which can be visualized as relative changes in pit length.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] (CAV), also known as Standard Play, offered several advanced playback features, including freeze-frame, variable slow motion, and reverse playback.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] rpm for PAL, with one video frame read per revolution.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] between adjacent tracks, as any interference would occur at the same point in adjacent frames.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Although less common than constant linear velocity (CLV) discs, CAV was often used for special edition releases to showcase bonus features and effects.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Notably, each frame on a CAV disc could be referenced by number, a feature valued by film scholars and enthusiasts for studying continuity, staging, and production details.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] , which could simulate functions like freeze-frame and variable-speed playback.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] CLV discs gradually slowed their rotational speed during playback to increase storage capacity, ranging from 1,800 to 600 rpm for NTSC, and 2,470 to 935 rpm for Hi-Vision.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This allowed up to 60 minutes of video per side for NTSC and Hi-Vision formats (64 minutes for PAL), or up to two hours per disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] For films under two hours, the entire feature could fit on a single disc, which reduced production costs and removed the need to change discs mid-movie, especially convenient for users with dual-sided players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Most LaserDisc titles were released in CLV format, though some used a mix, with one side in CLV and the other in CAV.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This allowed selected scenes, such as the climax or bonus features, to be presented in CAV, enabling frame-accurate navigation and highlighting special effects.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] (CAA) was introduced in the early 1980s to address crosstalk distortion and tracking issues found in CLV discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Unlike CLV, which slows the disc gradually, CAA changes the rotation speed in controlled steps, improving playback while remaining compatible with existing players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Most disc manufacturers switched to CAA, though the term rarely appeared on consumer packaging.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] When digital audio was added to LaserDisc in 1985, it created bandwidth issues with CAA, reducing playback time to 55 minutes per side.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] As a result, some movies included only analog audio to fit the entire film on one disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By 1987, Pioneer improved the CAA format to support a full 60 minutes of video with digital audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer also extended CAA disc playback to 65 minutes per side for a few titles and developed a 70-minute format, though this longer version was never used commercially.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Sound could be stored in either analog or digital format and in a variety of surround sound formats; NTSC discs could carry a stereo analog audio track, plus a stereo CD-quality uncompressed PCM digital audio track, which were (EFM, CIRC, 16-bit and 44.1 kHz sample rate).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] PAL discs could carry one pair of audio tracks, either analog or digital and the digital tracks on a PAL disc were 16-bit, 44.1 kHz as on a CD; in the UK, the term "LaserVision" is used to refer to discs with analog sound, while "LaserDisc" is used for those with digital audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The digital sound signal in both formats is EFM-encoded, as in CD.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Unlike DVDs, which carry Dolby Digital audio in digital form, LaserDiscs stored Dolby Digital in a frequency modulated form within a track normally used for analog audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Extracting Dolby Digital from a LaserDisc required a player equipped with a special "AC-3 RF" output and an external demodulator in addition to an AC-3 decoder.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The demodulator was necessary to convert the 2.88 MHz modulated AC-3 information on the disc into a 384 kbit/s signal that the decoder could handle.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In the mid to late 1990s, many higher-end AV receivers included the demodulator circuit specifically for the LaserDisc player's RF-modulated Dolby Digital AC-3 signal.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By the late 1990s, with LaserDisc players and disc sales declining due to DVD's growing popularity, the AV receiver manufacturers removed the demodulator circuit.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Although DVD players were capable of playing Dolby Digital tracks, the signals out of DVD players were not in a modulated form and were not compatible with the inputs designed for LaserDisc AC-3.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Outboard demodulators were available for a period that converted the AC-3 signal to the standard Dolby Digital signal that was compatible with the standard Dolby Digital/PCM inputs on capable AV receivers.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Another type marketed by Onkyo and Marantz converted the RF AC-3 signal to 6-channel analog audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] At least where the digital audio tracks were concerned, the sound quality was unsurpassed at the time compared to consumer videotape.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] However, the quality of the analog soundtracks could vary greatly depending upon the disc and, sometimes, the player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many early and lower-end LaserDisc players had poor analog audio components, and in turn, many early discs had poorly mastered analog audio tracks, making digital soundtracks in any form more desirable to serious enthusiasts.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Early DiscoVision and LaserDisc titles lacked the digital audio option, but many of those movies received digital sound in later re-issues by Universal, and the quality of analog audio tracks generally improved greatly as time went on.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many discs that had originally carried old analog stereo tracks received new Dolby Stereo and Dolby Surround tracks instead often in addition to digital tracks, which helped boost sound quality.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Later analog discs also applied CX noise reduction, which improved the signal-to-noise ratio of the audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] DTS audio, when available on a disc, replaced the digital audio tracks; hearing DTS-encoded audio required only an S/PDIF compliant digital connection to a DTS decoder.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] On a DTS disc, digital PCM audio was not available, so if a DTS decoder was also not available, the only option was to fall back to the analog Dolby Surround or stereo audio tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In some cases, the analog audio tracks were further made unavailable through replacement with supplementary audio such as isolated scores or audio commentary.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This effectively reduced playback of a DTS disc on a non-DTS equipped system to mono audio, or in a handful of cases, no film soundtrack at all.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Only one 5.1 surround sound option existed on a given LaserDisc (either Dolby Digital or DTS).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] As such, if surround sound was desired, the disc must be matched to the capabilities of the playback equipment (LaserDisc player and receiver/decoder) by the purchaser.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many 1990s A/V receivers combined the AC-3 decoder and DTS decoder logic, but an integrated AC-3 demodulator was rare both in LaserDisc players and in later A/V receivers.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] PAL LaserDiscs have a slightly longer playing time than NTSC discs, but have fewer audio options.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] PAL discs only have two audio tracks, consisting of either two analog-only tracks on older PAL LaserDiscs, or two digital-only tracks on newer discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In comparison, later NTSC LaserDiscs are capable of carrying four tracks (two analog and two digital).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] On certain releases, one of the analog tracks is used to carry a modulated AC-3 signal for 5.1 channel audio (for decoding and playback by newer LaserDisc players with an "AC-3 RF" output).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Older NTSC LaserDiscs made before 1984 (such as the original DiscoVision discs) only have two analog audio tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The earliest players employed gas helium–neon laser tubes to read discs and had a red-orange light with a wavelength of 632.8 nm, while later solid-state players used infrared semiconductor laser diodes with a wavelength of 780 nm.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In March 1984, Pioneer introduced the first consumer player with a solid-state laser, the LD-700.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] It was also the first LaserDisc player to load from the front and not the top.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] One year earlier, Hitachi introduced an expensive industrial player with a laser diode, but the player had poor picture quality (due to an inadequate dropout compensator), and was made only in limited quantities.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] After Pioneer released the LD-700, gas lasers were no longer used in consumer players, despite their advantages, although Philips continued to use gas lasers in their industrial units until 1985.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Most LaserDisc players required the user to manually turn the disc over to play the other side.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A number of players (all diode laser based) were made that were capable of playing both sides of the disc automatically, using a mechanism to physically flip a single laser pickup.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer produced some multi-disc models which held more than 50 LaserDiscs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] For a short time in 1984, one company offered a "LaserStack" unit that added multi-disc capability to existing players: the Pioneer LD-600, LD-1100, or the Sylvania/Magnavox clones.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] It required the user to physically remove the player lid for installation, where it then attached to the top of the player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserStack held up to 10 discs and could automatically load or remove them from the player or change sides in around 15 seconds.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The first mass-produced industrial LaserDisc player was the MCA DiscoVision PR-7820, later rebranded the Pioneer PR7820.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In North America, this unit was used in many General Motors dealerships as a source of training videos and presentation of GM's new line of cars and trucks in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Most players made after the mid-1980s were capable of also playing Compact Discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] These players included a 4.7 in (12 cm) indentation in the loading tray, where the CD was placed for playback.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] At least two Pioneer models (the CLD-M301 and the CLD-M90) also operated as a CD changer, with several 4.7 in indentations around the circumference of the main tray.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The Pioneer DVL-9, introduced in 1996, was both Pioneer's first consumer DVD player and the first combination DVD/LD player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The first high-definition video player was the Pioneer HLD-X0.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A later model, the HLD-X9, featured a superior comb filter, and laser diodes on both sides of the disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] During its development, MCA (which co-owned the technology), referred to it as the *Optical Videodisc System*, "Reflective Optical Videodisc" or "Laser Optical Videodisc", depending on the document.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] They changed the name once in 1969 to *Disco-Vision* and then again in 1978 to *DiscoVision* (without the hyphen), which became the official spelling.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Technical documents and brochures produced by MCA Disco-Vision during the early and mid-'70s also used the term "Disco-Vision Records" to refer to the pressed discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Philips' preferred name for the format was "VLP", after the Dutch words Video Langspeel-Plaat ("Video long-play disc"), which in English-speaking countries stood for Video Long-Play.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The first consumer player, the Magnavox VH-8000 even had the VLP logo on the player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] For a while in the early and mid-1970s, Philips also discussed a compatible audio-only format they called "ALP", but that was soon dropped as the Compact Disc system became a non-compatible project in the Philips corporation.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Until early 1980, the format had no "official" name.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The LaserVision Association, made up of MCA, Universal-Pioneer, IBM, and Philips/Magnavox, was formed to standardize the technical specifications of the format (which had been causing problems for the consumer market) and finally named the system officially as "LaserVision".
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] After its introduction in Japan in 1981, the format was introduced in Europe in 1983 with the LaserVision name, although Philips used "VLP" in model designations, such as VLP-600.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Following lackluster sales there (around 12–15,000 units Europe-wide), Philips tried relaunching the entire format as "CD-Video" in 1987, with the name appearing not just on the new hybrid 12 cm discs, but also on standard 20 and 30 cm LaserDiscs with digital audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] While this name and logo appeared on players and labels for years, the "official" name of the format remained LaserVision.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In the early 1990s, the format's name was changed again to LaserDisc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer Electronics also entered the optical disc market in 1977 as a 50/50 joint venture with MCA called Universal-Pioneer and manufacturing MCA-designed industrial players under the MCA DiscoVision name (the PR-7800 and PR-7820).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] For the 1980 launch of the first Universal-Pioneer player, the VP-1000 was noted as a "laser disc player", although the "LaserDisc" logo was displayed clearly on the device.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In 1981, "LaserDisc" was used exclusively for the medium itself, although the official name was "LaserVision" (as seen at the beginning of many LaserDisc releases, just before the start of the film).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Pioneer reminded numerous video magazines and stores in 1984 that LaserDisc was a trademarked word, standing only for LaserVision products manufactured for sale by Pioneer Video or Pioneer Electronics.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] A 1984 Ray Charles ad for the LD-700 player bore the term "Pioneer LaserDisc brand videodisc player".
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] From 1981 until the early 1990s, all properly licensed discs carried the LaserVision name and logo, even Pioneer Artists titles.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] On single-sided LaserDiscs mastered by Pioneer, playing the wrong side would cause a still screen to appear with a happy, upside-down turtle that has a LaserDisc for a belly (nicknamed "Flippy").
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The words "Program material is recorded on the other side of this disc" are below the turtle.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This also appears on Japanese releases, with the text in Japanese.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] During the early years, MCA also manufactured discs for other companies including Paramount, Disney and Warner Bros.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some of them added their own names to the disc jacket to signify that the movie was not owned by MCA.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] After DiscoVision Associates shut down in early 1982, Universal Studio's videodisc software label (called *MCA Videodisc* until 1984), began reissuing many DiscoVision titles.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Unfortunately, quite a few, such as *Battlestar Galactica* and *Jaws*, were time-compressed versions of their CAV or CLV DiscoVision originals.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The time-compressed CLV re-issue of *Jaws* no longer had the original soundtrack, having had incidental background music replaced for the videodisc version due to high licensing costs (the original music would not be available until the THX LaserDisc box set was released in 1995).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] An MCA release of Universal's *Howard the Duck* shows only the start credits shown in widescreen before changing to 4:3 for the rest of the film.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] For many years, this was the only disc-based release of the film, until widescreen DVD formats were released with extras.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Also, the 1989 and 1996 LaserDisc releases of *E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial* are the only formats to include the cut scene of Harrison Ford, in the role of the school principal, telling off Elliott for letting the frogs free in the biology class.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc had several advantages over VHS.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] It featured a far sharper picture with a horizontal resolution of 425 television lines (TVL) for NTSC and 440 TVL for PAL discs, while VHS featured only 240 TVL with NTSC.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Super VHS, released in 1987, reduced the quality gap, having horizontal luma resolution comparable to LaserDisc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] But horizontal chroma resolution of Super VHS remained as low as that of standard VHS, about 40 TVL, while LaserDisc offered about 70 TVL of chroma resolution.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc could handle analog and digital audio where VHS was mostly analog only (VHS could have PCM audio in professional applications but it was uncommon), and the NTSC discs could store multiple audio tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This allowed for extras such as director's commentary tracks and other features to be added onto a film, creating "Special Edition" releases that would not have been possible with VHS.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Disc access was random and chapter-based, like the DVD format, meaning that one could jump to any point on a given disc very quickly.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By comparison, VHS would require rewinding and fast-forwarding to get to specific points.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDiscs potentially had a much longer lifespan than videocassettes.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Because the discs were read optically instead of magnetically, no physical contact needed to be made between the player and the disc, except for the player's clamp that holds the disc at its center as it is spun and read.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] As a result, playback would not wear the information-bearing part of the discs, and properly manufactured LaserDiscs could theoretically last beyond a lifetime.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By contrast, a VHS tape held all of its picture and sound information on the tape in a magnetic coating which was in contact with the spinning heads on the head drum, causing progressive wear with each use.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The tape was also thin and delicate, and it was easy for a player mechanism, especially on a low quality or malfunctioning model, to mishandle the tape and damage it by creasing it, frilling (stretching) its edges, or even breaking it.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc was a composite video format: the luminance (black and white) and chrominance (color) information were transmitted in one signal, separated by the receiver.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] While good comb filters could separate the signals adequately, the two signals could not be *completely* separated.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In contrast to the entirely digital DVD, LaserDiscs used only analog video.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Early DVD releases held the potential to surpass their LaserDisc counterparts, but often managed only to match them for image quality, and in some cases, the LaserDisc version was preferred.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Proprietary human-assisted encoders manually operated by specialists could vastly reduce the incidence of artifacts, depending on playing time and image complexity.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By the end of LaserDisc's run, DVDs were living up to their potential as a superior format.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] DVDs use compressed audio formats such as Dolby Digital and DTS for multichannel sound.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Most LaserDiscs were encoded with stereo (often Dolby Surround) CD quality audio 16bit/44.1 kHz tracks as well as analog audio tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] DTS-encoded LaserDiscs have DTS soundtracks of 1,235 kbit/s instead of the reduced bitrate of 768 kbit/s commonly employed on DVDs with optional DTS audio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc players could provide a greater degree of control over the playback process.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Unlike many DVD players, the transport mechanism always obeyed commands from the user: pause, fast-forward, and fast-reverse commands were always accepted (barring malfunctions).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] There were no "User Prohibited Options" where content protection code instructed the player to refuse commands to skip a specific part (such as fast forwarding through copyright warnings).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] With CAV LaserDiscs, the user could jump directly to any individual frame of a video simply by entering the frame number on the remote keypad, a feature not common among DVD players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some DVD players have a cache feature, which stores a certain amount of the video in RAM, which allows the player to index a DVD as quickly as an LD, even down to the frame in some players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Damaged spots on a LaserDisc could be played through or skipped over, while a DVD will often become unplayable past the damage.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some newer DVD players feature a repair+skip algorithm, which alleviates this problem by continuing to play the disc, filling in unreadable areas of the picture with blank space or a frozen frame of the last readable image and sound.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The success of this feature depends upon the amount of damage.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc players, when working in full analog, recover from such errors faster than DVD players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Similar to the CD versus LP sound quality debates common in the audiophile community, some videophiles argue that LaserDisc maintains a "smoother", more "film-like", natural image while DVD still looks slightly more artificial.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Early DVD demo discs often had compression or encoding problems, lending additional support to such claims at the time.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The video signal-to-noise ratio and bandwidth of LaserDisc are substantially less than those of DVDs, making DVDs appear sharper and clearer to most viewers.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Another advantage, at least to some consumers, was the fact that any sort of anti-piracy technology was purely optional.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] It was claimed that Macrovision's Analog Protection System could not be applied to LaserDisc, due to the format's design.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The vertical blanking interval, where the Macrovision signal would be implemented, was used for timecode and frame coding as well as player control codes on LaserDisc players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Due to its relatively small market share, there was never a push to redesign the format despite the obvious potential for piracy.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The industry simply decided to engineer it into the DVD specification.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The disc provided interviews, commentary tracks, documentaries, still photographs, and other features for historians and collectors.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Also, because of their size, greater mechanical effort was required to spin the discs at the proper speed, resulting in much more noise generated than other media.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] After one side finished playing, a disc had to be flipped over to continue watching a movie, and some titles filled two or more discs, depending on the film's runtime and whether or not special features are included.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many players, especially units built after the mid-1980s, could "flip" discs automatically (by rotating the optical pickup to the other side of the disc), but this was accompanied by a pause in the movie during the side change.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In addition, perfect still frames and random access to individual still frames was limited only to the more expensive CAV discs, which only had a playing time of approximately 30 minutes per side.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In later years, Pioneer and other manufacturers overcame this limitation by incorporating a digital memory buffer, which "grabbed" a single field or frame from a CLV disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The analog information encoded onto LaserDiscs also did not include any form of built-in checksum or error correction.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Because of this, slight dust and scratches on the disc surface could result in read errors which caused various video quality problems: glitches, streaks, bursts of static, or momentary picture interruptions.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In contrast, the digital MPEG-2 format information used on DVDs has built-in error correction which ensures that the signal from a damaged disc will remain identical to that from a perfect disc right up until the damage to the disc surface prevents the laser from being able to identify usable data.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In addition, LaserDisc videos sometimes exhibited a problem known as "crosstalk".
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The issue could arise when the laser optical pickup assembly within the player was out of alignment or because the disc was damaged or excessively warped.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] But it could also occur even with a properly functioning player and a factory-new disc, depending on electrical and mechanical alignment problems.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In these instances, the issue arose due to the fact that CLV discs required subtle changes in rotating speed at various points during playback.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Assuming the player's optical pickup was in proper working order, crosstalk distortion normally did not occur during playback of CAV-format LaserDiscs, as the rotational speed never varied.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] If the player calibration was out of order, or if the CAV disc was faulty or damaged, other problems affecting tracking accuracy could occur.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] One such problem was "laser lock", where the player read the same two fields for a given frame over and over, causing the picture to look frozen as if the movie were paused.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Another significant issue unique to LaserDisc involved the inconsistency of playback quality between different makers and models of player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] In contrast, LaserDisc playback quality was highly dependent on hardware quality, and major variances in picture quality appeared between different makers and models of LaserDisc players, even when tested on low- to mid-range televisions.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Many early LaserDiscs were not manufactured properly.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The adhesive that was used contained impurities which were able to penetrate the lacquer seal layer and chemically attack the metalized reflective aluminum layer, altering its reflective characteristics.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This, in turn, deteriorated the recorded signal.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This was a problem that was termed "laser rot" among LaserDisc enthusiasts (also called "color flash" internally by LaserDisc pressing plants).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some forms of laser rot could appear as black spots that looked like mold or burned plastic which caused the disc to skip and the video to exhibit excessive speckling noise.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] But, for the most part, rotted discs could actually appear perfectly fine to the naked eye.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Later optical standards have also been known to suffer similar problems, including a notorious batch of defective CDs manufactured by Philips-DuPont Optical at their Blackburn, Lancashire facility in England during the late 1980s/early 1990s.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] LaserDisc did not have high market penetration in North America due to the high cost of the players and discs (which were far more expensive than VHS players and tapes), and due to marketplace confusion with the technologically inferior CED, which also went by the name Videodisc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] While the format was not widely adopted by North American consumers, it was received well among videophiles due to the superior audio and video quality compared to VHS and Betamax tapes, thus finding a place in nearly one million American homes by the end of 1990.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The format was more popular in Japan than in North America because prices were kept low to ensure adoption, resulting in minimal price differences between VHS tapes and the higher quality LaserDiscs, which helped ensure that it quickly became the dominant consumer video format in Japan.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Anime collectors in every country in which the LaserDisc format was released (which included both North America and Japan) also quickly became familiar with this format, and sought the higher video and sound quality of LaserDisc and the availability of numerous titles not available on VHS.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The format also became quite popular in Hong Kong during the 1990s before the introduction of VCDs and DVD.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] While people rarely bought the discs (because each LaserDisc was priced around US$100), high rental activity helped the video rental business in the city grow larger than it had ever been previously.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Due to integration with the Japanese export market, NTSC LaserDiscs were used in the Hong Kong market, in contrast to the PAL standard used for broadcast (this anomaly also exists for DVD).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This created a market for multi-system TVs and multi-system VCRs which could display or play both PAL and NTSC materials in addition to SECAM materials (which were never popular in Hong Kong).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Some LaserDisc players could convert NTSC signals to PAL during playback so that TVs used in Hong Kong could display the LaserDisc materials.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Despite the relative popularity, manufacturers refused to market recordable LaserDisc devices on the consumer market, even though the competing VCR devices could record onto cassette.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This had a negative impact on sales worldwide.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The inconvenient disc size, the high cost of both the players and the media and the inability to record onto the discs combined to take a serious toll on sales, and contributed to the format's poor adoption figures.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] By 1995, several companies began to invest in the developing DVD and knew that the future of LaserDisc was to be short-lived.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] The Video Software Dealers Association (VSDA) Convention in the middle of 1996 though highlighted the mixed consensus by some executives whether or not LaserDisc could be replaced by DVD.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Throughout 1996, knowledge about DVD spread through the public and the sale of LaserDisc players was already noticeably diminishing by 1996.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Nevertheless, sales of LaserDiscs titles stood relatively firm (though with a small decline) around the same time.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] This was aided by the delayed release of DVD which was supposed to occur around Labor Day Weekend, 1996.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p01] Until the end of 2001, many titles were released on VHS, LaserDisc, and DVD in Japan.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In the early 1980s, Philips produced a LaserDisc player model adapted for a computer interface, dubbed "professional." In 1985, Jasmine Multimedia created LaserDisc jukeboxes featuring music videos from Michael Jackson, Duran Duran, and Cyndi Lauper.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] When connected to a PC this combination could be used to display images or information for educational or archival purposes, for example, thousands of scanned medieval manuscripts.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] This device could be considered a very early equivalent of a CD-ROM.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In the mid-1980s Lucasfilm pioneered the EditDroid non-linear editing system for film and television based on computer-controlled LaserDisc players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Instead of printing dailies out on film, processed negatives from the day's shoot would be sent to a mastering plant to be assembled from their 10-minute camera elements into 20-minute film segments.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These were then mastered onto single-sided blank LaserDiscs, just as a DVD would be burnt at home today, allowing for much easier selection and preparation of an edit decision list (EDL).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In the days before video assist was available in cinematography, this was the only other way a film crew could see their work.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The EDL went to the negative cutter who then cut the camera negative accordingly and assembled the finished film.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Only 24 EditDroid systems were ever built, even though the ideas and technology are still in use today.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Later EditDroid experiments borrowed from hard-drive technology of having multiple discs on the same spindle and added numerous playback heads and numerous electronics to the basic jukebox design so that any point on each of the discs would be accessible within seconds.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] This eliminated the need for racks and racks of industrial LaserDisc players since EditDroid discs were only single-sided.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In 1986, a SCSI-equipped LaserDisc player attached to a BBC Master computer was used for the BBC Domesday Project.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The player was referred as an LV-ROM (LaserVision Read Only Memory) as the discs contained the driving software as well as the video frames.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The discs used the CAV format, and encoded data as a binary signal represented by the analog audio recording.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These discs could contain in each CAV frame video/audio or video/binary data, but not both.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] "Data" frames would appear blank when played as video.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] It was typical for each disc to start with the disc catalog (a few blank frames) then the video introduction before the rest of the data.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Because the format (based on the ADFS hard disc format) used a starting sector for each file, the data layout effectively skipped over any video frames.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] If all 54,000 frames are used for data storage an LV-ROM disc can contain 324 MB of data per side.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The Domesday Project systems also included a genlock, allowing video frames, clips and audio to be mixed with graphics originated from the BBC Master; this was used to great effect for displaying high-resolution photographs and maps, which could then be zoomed into.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] During the 1980s in the United States, Digital Equipment Corporation developed the standalone PC control IVIS (Interactive VideoDisc Information System) for training and education.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] One of the most influential programs developed at DEC was Decision Point, a management gaming simulation, which won the Nebraska Video Disc Award for Best of Show in 1985.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Apple's HyperCard scripting language provided Macintosh computer users with a means to design databases of slides, animation, video and sounds from LaserDiscs and then to create interfaces for users to play specific content from the disc through software called LaserStacks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] User-created "stacks" were shared and were especially popular in education where teacher-generated stacks were used to access discs ranging from art collections to basic biological processes.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Commercially available stacks were also popular with the Voyager company being possibly the most successful distributor.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Commodore International's 1992 multimedia presentation system for the Amiga, AmigaVision, included device drivers for controlling a number of LaserDisc players through a serial port.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Coupled with the Amiga's ability to use a Genlock, this allowed for the LaserDisc video to be overlaid with computer graphics and integrated into presentations and multimedia displays, years before such practice was commonplace.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Pioneer also made computer-controlled units such as the LD-V2000.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] It had a back-panel RS-232 serial connection through a five-pin DIN connector, and no front-panel controls except *Open/Close*.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Under contract from the U.S. military, Matrox produced a combination computer/LaserDisc player for instructional purposes.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The computer was a 286, the LaserDisc player only capable of reading the analog audio tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Together they weighed 43 lb (20 kg) and sturdy handles were provided in case two people were required to lift the unit.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The computer controlled the player via a 25-pin serial port at the back of the player and a ribbon cable connected to a proprietary port on the motherboard.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Many of these were sold as surplus by the military during the 1990s, often without the controller software.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Nevertheless, it is possible to control the unit by removing the ribbon cable and connecting a serial cable directly from the computer's serial port to the port on the LaserDisc player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The format's instant-access capability made it possible for a new breed of LaserDisc-based video arcade games.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Several companies saw potential in using LaserDiscs for video games in the 1980s and 1990s, beginning in 1983 with Sega's *Astron Belt*.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Cinematronics and American Laser Games produced elaborate arcade games that used the random-access features to create interactive movies such as *Dragon's Lair* and *Space Ace*.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Similarly, the Pioneer Laseractive and Halcyon were introduced as home video game consoles that used LaserDisc media for their software.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In 1991, several manufacturers announced specifications for what would become known as **Hi-Vision LD**, representing a span of almost 15 years until the feats of this HD analog optical disc system would finally be duplicated digitally by HD DVD and Blu-ray Disc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Encoded using NHK's MUSE "Hi-Vision" analog HDTV system, MUSE discs would operate like standard LaserDiscs but would contain high-definition 1,125-line (1,035 visible lines; Sony HDVS) video with a 16:9 aspect ratio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The MUSE players were also capable of playing standard NTSC format discs and are superior in performance to non-MUSE players even with these NTSC discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The MUSE-capable players had several noteworthy advantages over standard LaserDisc players, including a red laser with a much narrower wavelength than the lasers found in standard players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The red laser was capable of reading through disc defects such as scratches and even mild disc rot that would cause most other players to stop, stutter or drop-out.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Crosstalk was not an issue with MUSE discs, and the narrow wavelength of the laser allowed for the virtual elimination of crosstalk with normal discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] To view MUSE-encoded discs, it was necessary to have a MUSE decoder in addition to a compatible player.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] There are televisions with MUSE decoding built-in and set-top tuners with decoders that can provide the proper MUSE input.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Equipment prices were high, especially for early HDTVs which generally eclipsed US$10,000, and even in Japan the market for MUSE was tiny.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Players and discs were never officially sold in North America, although several distributors imported MUSE discs along with other import titles.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] *Terminator 2: Judgment Day*, *Lawrence of Arabia*, *A League of Their Own*, *Bugsy*, *Close Encounters of the Third Kind*, *Bram Stoker's Dracula* and *Chaplin* were among the theatrical releases available on MUSE LDs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Several documentaries, including one about Formula One at Japan's Suzuka Circuit were also released.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] LaserDisc players and LaserDiscs that worked with the competing European HD-MAC HDTV standard were also made.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Picture discs have artistic etching on one side of the disc to make the disc more visually attractive than the standard shiny silver surface.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] This etching might look like a movie character, logo, or other promotional material.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Sometimes that side of the LD would be made with colored plastic, rather than the clear material used for the data side.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Picture disc LDs only had video material on one side as the "picture" side could not contain any data.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Picture discs are rare in North America.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Pioneer Electronics—one of the format's largest supporters/investors—was also deeply involved in the karaoke business in Japan, and used LaserDiscs as the storage medium for music and additional content such as graphics.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] While several other karaoke labels manufactured LaserDiscs, there was nothing like the breadth of competition in that industry that exists now, as almost all manufacturers have transitioned to CD+G discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] With the release of 16:9 televisions in the early 1990s, Pioneer and Toshiba decided that it was time to take advantage of this aspect ratio.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Squeeze LDs were enhanced 16:9-ratio widescreen LaserDiscs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] During the video transfer stage, the movie was stored in an anamorphic "squeezed" format.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The widescreen movie image was stretched to fill the entire video frame with less or none of the video resolution wasted to create letterbox bars.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The advantage was a 33% greater vertical resolution compared to letterboxed widescreen LaserDisc.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] This same procedure was used for anamorphic DVDs, but unlike all DVD players, very few LD players had the ability to unsqueeze the image for 4:3 sets, If the discs were played on a standard 4:3 television the image would be distorted.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Some 4:3 sets (such as the Sony WEGA series) could be set to unsqueeze the image.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Since very few people outside of Japan owned 16:9 displays, the marketability of these special discs was very limited.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] There were no anamorphic LaserDisc titles available in the US except for promotional purposes.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Upon purchase of a Toshiba 16:9 television viewers had the option of selecting a number of Warner Bros.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Titles include *Unforgiven*, *Grumpy Old Men*, *The Fugitive*, and *Free Willy*.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The Japanese lineup of titles was different.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] A series of releases under the banner "Squeeze LD" from Pioneer of mostly Carolco titles included *Basic Instinct*, *Stargate*, *Terminator 2: Judgment Day*, *Showgirls*, *Cutthroat Island*, and *Cliffhanger*.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] *Terminator 2* was released twice in Squeeze LD, the second release being THX certified and a notable improvement over the first.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Several recordable variants of the LaserDisc format were developed for professional and industrial applications, but none were marketed to consumers.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Their limited availability contributed to the common perception that LaserDisc lacked recording capability.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The **Recordable Laser Videodisc** (**RLV**), introduced by the Optical Disc Corporation in 1984, was a write-once, read-many format that was fully compatible with standard LaserDisc players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Compared to conventional LaserDiscs, RLVs were distinguished by a red/purple tint of the dye used in the reflective layer that is burned by the laser.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The **Component Recordable Video disc** (**CRVdisc**), developed by Sony, was another write-once, read-many format intended for professional use.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Housed in a protective caddy, the disc resembled an oversized floppy disk.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The CRVdisc was used by the BBC for many years to playout idents.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The **LaserRecorder**, introduced by Pioneer in fall 1991, was a rewritable LaserDisc system designed for professional video production.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] It used CAV mode and protective caddies, with discs, which could hold 32 minutes of video per side, were rated for up to one million record/erase cycles.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The dual-laser design enabled real-time, frame-accurate non-linear editing by allowing one laser to read while the other searched.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The system's rapid access made it useful for editing workflows, including its integration into EditDroid, an early digital film editing system.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The recorder sold for around US$39,950 (equivalent to $91,657 in 2025), with blank discs priced at approximately US$1,295 (equivalent to $2,971 in 2025).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The most common size of LaserDisc was 30 cm (11.8 in), approximately the size of 12 in (30.5 cm) LP vinyl records.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These discs allowed for 30/36 minutes per side (CAV NTSC/PAL) or 60/64 minutes per side (CLV NTSC/PAL).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The vast majority of programming for the LaserDisc format was produced on these discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] A number of 20 cm (7.9 in) LaserDiscs were also published.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These smaller "EP"-sized LDs allowed for 20 minutes per side (CLV).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] They are much rarer than the full-size LDs, especially in North America, and roughly approximate the size of 45 rpm (7 in (17.8 cm)) vinyl singles.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These discs were often used for music video compilations (e.g.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Bon Jovi's "Breakout" and Bananarama's "Video Singles") as well as Japanese karaoke machines.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] There were also 12 cm (4.7 in) (CD size) "single"-style discs produced that were playable on LaserDisc players.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] These were referred to as CD Video (CD-V) discs, and Video Single Discs (VSD).
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] CD-V was a hybrid format launched in the late 1980s, and carried up to five minutes of analog LaserDisc-type video content with a digital soundtrack (usually a music video), plus up to 20 minutes of digital audio CD tracks.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The original 1989 release of David Bowie's retrospective *Sound + Vision* CD box set prominently featured a CD-V video of "Ashes to Ashes", and standalone promo CD-Vs featured the video, plus three audio tracks: "John, I'm Only Dancing", "Changes", and "The Supermen".
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Despite the similar name, CD Video is entirely incompatible with the later all-digital Video CD (VCD) format, and can only be played back on LaserDisc players with CD-V capability or one of the players dedicated to the smaller discs.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] In Europe, Philips also used the "CD Video" name as part of a short-lived attempt in the late 1980s to relaunch and rebrand the entire LaserDisc system.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] Some 20 and 30 cm discs were also branded "CD Video", but unlike the 12 cm discs, these were essentially just standard LaserDiscs with digital soundtracks and no audio-only CD content.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] The VSD format was announced in 1990, and was essentially the same as the 12 cm (4.7 in) CD-V, but without the audio CD tracks, and intended to sell at a lower price.
[src:american-memory/laserdisc-p02] VSDs were popular only in Japan and other parts of Asia and were never fully introduced to the rest of the world.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The **Library of Congress** (**LOC**) is a research library in Washington, D.C., serving as the library and research service for the United States Congress and the *de facto* national library of the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It also administers copyright law through the United States Copyright Office, and it houses the Congressional Research Service.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Founded in 1800, the Library of Congress is the oldest federal cultural institution in the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It is housed in three buildings on Capitol Hill, adjacent to the United States Capitol, along with the National Audio-Visual Conservation Center in Culpeper, Virginia, and additional storage facilities at Fort George G.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Meade and Cabin Branch in Hyattsville, Maryland.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library's functions are overseen by the librarian of Congress, and its buildings are maintained by the architect of the Capitol.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library is one of the largest libraries in the world, containing approximately 173 million items and employing over 3,000 staff.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Its collections are "universal, not limited by subject, format, or national boundary, and include research materials from all parts of the world and in more than 470 languages".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] When Congress moved to Washington in November 1800, a small congressional library was housed in the Capitol.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Much of the original collection was lost during the 1814 burning of Washington by British forces during the War of 1812.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress accepted former president Thomas Jefferson's offer to sell his entire personal collection of 6,487 books to restore the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The collection grew slowly and suffered another major fire in 1851, which destroyed two-thirds of Jefferson's original books.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress faced space shortages, understaffing, and lack of funding, until the American Civil War increased the importance of legislative research to meet the demands of a growing federal government.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1870, the library gained the right to receive two copies of every copyrightable work printed in the United States; it also built its collections through acquisitions and donations.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Between 1890 and 1897, a new library building, now the Thomas Jefferson Building, was constructed.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Two additional buildings, the John Adams Building (opened in 1939) and the James Madison Memorial Building (opened in 1980), were later added.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The LC's Congressional Research Service provides objective non-partisan research to Congress to assist it in passing legislation.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library is open to the public for research, although only members of Congress, their staff, and library employees may borrow materials for use outside the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1783, James Madison, a Founding Father and the nation's fourth president, proposed creating a congressional library, but failed to gain necessary support for the idea.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] After the American Revolutionary War, however, the Philadelphia Library Company and New York Society Library served as surrogate congressional libraries when Congress convened in those cities.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Adams' successor as U.S. president, Thomas Jefferson, also played a crucial role in shaping development of the Library of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On January 26, 1802, Jefferson signed a bill allowing the president to appoint the librarian of Congress and establishing a Joint Committee on the Library to oversee it.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The law also extended borrowing privileges to the president and vice president.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In August 1814, British forces occupied Washington and, in retaliation for American acts of destruction in Canada, burned several federal government buildings.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Among the buildings burnt was the Library of Congress, which saw over 3,000 of its volumes destroyed.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] These volumes were held in the Senate wing of the Capitol; one surviving volume was a government account book from 1810.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The volume was taken by British Admiral George Cockburn as a souvenir, and was later returned to the U.S. in 1940 by his family.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Within a month, Jefferson offered to sell his large personal library as a replacement.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He had reconstituted his own collection after losing part of it to a fire.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress accepted the offer in January 1815, appropriating $23,950 to purchase his 6,487 books.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Some House members, including New Hampshire representative Daniel Webster, opposed the purchase, wanting to exclude "books of an atheistical, irreligious, and immoral tendency".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Jefferson's collection, gathered over 50 years, covered various subjects and languages, including topics not typically found in a legislative library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Jefferson's library was a working collection for a scholar, not for display.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It doubled the size of the original library, transforming it from a specialist's library to a more general one.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He organized his books based on Francis Bacon's organization of knowledge, grouping them into Memory, Reason, and Imagination with 44 subdivisions.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library used this scheme until the late 19th century when librarian Herbert Putnam introduced the Library of Congress Classification, now applying to over 138 million items.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] A February 24, 1824, report from the Committee of Ways and Means recommended a $5,000 appropriation for the Library of Congress, noting the need to improve its collections in "Law, Politics, Commerce, History, and Geography," which were crucial for Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On December 24, 1851, the largest fire in the library's history destroyed 35,000 books, two-thirds of the library's collection, and two-thirds of Thomas Jefferson's original transfer.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress appropriated $168,700 to replace the lost books in 1852 but not to acquire new materials.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Pearce, who restricted the library's activities.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Meehan and Pearce's views about a restricted scope for the Library of Congress reflected those shared by members of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] While Meehan was a librarian, he supported and perpetuated the notion that "the congressional library should play a limited role on the national scene and that its collections, by and large, should emphasize American materials of obvious use to the U.S.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress." In 1859, Congress transferred the library's public document distribution activities to the Department of the Interior and its international book exchange program to the Department of State.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] During the 1850s, Smithsonian Institution librarian Charles Coffin Jewett aggressively tried to develop the Smithsonian as the United States national library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] His efforts were rejected by Smithsonian secretary Joseph Henry, who advocated a focus on scientific research and publication.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] To reinforce his intentions for the Smithsonian, Henry established laboratories, developed a robust physical sciences library, and started the *Smithsonian Contributions to Knowledge*, the first of many publications intended to disseminate research results.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] For Henry, the Library of Congress was the obvious choice as the national library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Unable to resolve the conflict, Henry dismissed Jewett in July 1854.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1865, the Smithsonian building, also called the Castle due to its Norman architectural style, was severely damaged by fire.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This incident presented Henry with an opportunity related to the Smithsonian's non-scientific library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Around this time, the Library of Congress was planning to build and relocate to the new Thomas Jefferson Building, designed to be fireproof.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Authorized by an act of Congress, Henry transferred the Smithsonian's non-scientific library of 40,000 volumes to the Library of Congress in 1866.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1861, President Abraham Lincoln appointed John G.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Stephenson as Librarian of Congress; the appointment is regarded as the most political to date.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Stephenson was a physician and spent equal time serving as librarian and as a physician in the Union Army.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He could manage this division of interest because he hired Ainsworth Rand Spofford as his assistant.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Despite his new job, Stephenson focused on the war.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Three weeks into his term as Librarian of Congress, he left Washington, D.C., to serve as a volunteer aide-de-camp at the battles of Chancellorsville and Gettysburg during the American Civil War.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Stephenson's hiring of Spofford, who directed the library in his absence, may have been his most significant achievement.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Librarian Ainsworth Rand Spofford, who directed the Library of Congress from 1865 to 1897, built broad bipartisan support to develop it as a national library and a legislative resource.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He was aided by expansion of the federal government after the war and a favorable political climate.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He began comprehensively collecting Americana and American literature, led the construction of a new building to house the library, and transformed the librarian of Congress position into one of strength and independence.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Between 1865 and 1870, Congress appropriated funds for the construction of the Thomas Jefferson Building, placed all copyright registration and deposit activities under the library's control, and restored the international book exchange.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library also acquired the vast libraries of the Smithsonian and of historian Peter Force, strengthening its scientific and Americana collections significantly.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] By 1876, the Library of Congress had 300,000 volumes; it was tied with the Boston Public Library as the nation's largest library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It moved from the Capitol building to its new headquarters in 1897 with more than 840,000 volumes, 40 percent of which had been acquired through copyright deposit.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] A year before the library's relocation, the Joint Library Committee held hearings to assess the condition of the library and plan for its future growth and possible reorganization.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Spofford and six experts sent by the American Library Association testified that the library should continue its expansion to become a true national library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Based on the hearings, Congress authorized a budget that allowed the library to more than double its staff, from 42 to 108 persons.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Senators Justin Morrill of Vermont and Daniel W.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Voorhees of Indiana were particularly helpful in gaining this support.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library also established new administrative units for all aspects of the collection.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In its bill, Congress strengthened the role of librarian of Congress: it became responsible for governing the library and making staff appointments.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] As with presidential Cabinet appointments, the Senate was required to approve presidential appointees to the position.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1893, Elizabeth Dwyer became the first woman to be appointed to the staff of the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] With this support and the 1897 reorganization upon moving into its new home, the Library of Congress began to grow and develop more rapidly.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Librarian Young's successor Herbert Putnam held the office for forty years of the 20th century from 1899 to 1939.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Two years after he took office, the library became the first in the United States to hold one million volumes.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Putnam focused his efforts to make the library more accessible and useful for the public and for other libraries.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He instituted the interlibrary loan service, transforming the Library of Congress into what he referred to as a "library of last resort".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Putnam also expanded library access to "scientific investigators and duly qualified individuals", and began publishing primary sources for the benefit of scholars.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] During Putnam's tenure, the library broadened the diversity of its acquisitions.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1903, Putnam persuaded President Theodore Roosevelt to use an executive order to transfer the papers of the Founding Fathers from the State Department to the Library of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Putnam also expanded foreign acquisitions, including the 1904 purchase of a 4,000-volume library of Indica, the 1906 purchase of G.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Yudin's 80,000-volume Russian library, the 1908 Schatz collection of early opera librettos, and the early 1930s purchase of the Russian Imperial Collection, consisting of 2,600 volumes from the library of the Romanov family on a variety of topics.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Collections of Hebraica, Chinese, and Japanese works were also acquired.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On one occasion, Congress initiated an acquisition: in 1929 Congressman Ross Collins (D-Mississippi) gained approval for the library to purchase Otto Vollbehr's collection of incunabula for $1.5 million.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This collection included one of three remaining perfect vellum copies of the Gutenberg Bible.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Putnam established the Legislative Reference Service (LRS) in 1914 as a separative administrative unit of the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Based on the Progressive Era's philosophy of science to be used to solve problems, and modeled after successful research branches of state legislatures, the LRS would provide informed answers to Congressional research inquiries on almost any topic.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress passed in 1925 an act allowing the Library of Congress to establish a trust fund board to accept donations and endowments, giving the library a role as a patron of the arts.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library received donations and endowments by such prominent wealthy individuals as John D.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Gertrude Clarke Whittall donated five Stradivarius violins to the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge's donations paid for a concert hall to be constructed within the Library of Congress building and an honorarium established for the Music Division to pay live performers for concerts.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] A number of chairs and consultantships were established from the donations, the most well-known of which is the Poet Laureate Consultant.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library's expansion eventually filled the library's Main Building, although it used shelving expansions in 1910 and 1927.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library needed to expand into a new structure.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress acquired nearby land in 1928 and approved construction of the Annex Building (later known as the John Adams Building) in 1930.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Although delayed during the Depression years, it was completed in 1938 and opened to the public in 1939.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1939, following Putnam's retirement, President Franklin D.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Roosevelt appointed poet and writer Archibald MacLeish as his successor.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Occupying the post from 1939 to 1944 during the height of World War II, MacLeish became the most widely known librarian of Congress in the library's history.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] MacLeish encouraged librarians to oppose totalitarianism on behalf of democracy; dedicated the South Reading Room of the Adams Building to Thomas Jefferson, and commissioned artist Ezra Winter to paint four themed murals for the room.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He established a "democracy alcove" in the Main Reading Room of the Jefferson Building for essential documents such as the Declaration of Independence, the Constitution, and *The Federalist Papers*.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress assisted during the war effort, ranging from storage of the Declaration of Independence and the United States Constitution in Fort Knox for safekeeping to researching weather data on the Himalayas for Air Force pilots.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] MacLeish resigned in 1944 when appointed as Assistant Secretary of State.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] President Harry Truman appointed Luther H.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Evans, who served until 1953, expanded the library's acquisitions, cataloging, and bibliographic services.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] But he is best known for creating Library of Congress Missions worldwide.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Evans' successor Lawrence Quincy Mumford took over in 1953.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] During his tenure, lasting until 1974, Mumford directed the initiation of construction of the James Madison Memorial Building, the third Library of Congress building on Capitol Hill.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Mumford led the library during the government's increased educational spending.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library was able to establish new acquisition centers abroad, including in Cairo and New Delhi.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1967, the library began experimenting with book preservation techniques through a Preservation Office.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This has developed as the most extensive library research and conservation effort in the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] During Mumford's administration, the last significant public debate occurred about the Library of Congress's role as both a legislative and national library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Asked by Joint Library Committee chairman Senator Claiborne Pell (D-RI) to assess operations and make recommendations, Douglas Bryant of Harvard University Library proposed several institutional reforms.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] These included expanding national activities and services and various organizational changes, all of which would emphasize the library's federal role rather than its legislative role.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Bryant suggested changing the name of the Library of Congress, a recommendation rebuked by Mumford as "unspeakable violence to tradition." The debate continued within the library community for some time.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Legislative Reorganization Act of 1970 renewed emphasis for the library on its legislative roles, requiring a greater focus on research for Congress and congressional committees, and renaming the Legislative Reference Service as the Congressional Research Service.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] After Mumford retired in 1974, President Gerald Ford appointed historian Daniel J.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Boorstin's first challenge was to manage the relocation of some sections to the new Madison Building, which took place between 1980 and 1982.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] With this accomplished, Boorstin focused on other areas of library administration, such as acquisitions and collections.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Taking advantage of steady budgetary growth, from $116 million in 1975 to over $250 million by 1987, Boorstin enhanced institutional and staff ties with scholars, authors, publishers, cultural leaders, and the business community.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1987, President Ronald Reagan nominated historian James H.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Billington as the thirteenth librarian of Congress, and the U.S.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Senate unanimously confirmed the appointment.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Under Billington's leadership, the library doubled the size of its analog collections from 85.5 million items in 1987 to more than 160 million items in 2014.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] At the same time, it established new programs and employed new technologies to "get the champagne out of the bottle".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Since 1988, the library has administered the National Film Preservation Board.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Established by congressional mandate, it selects twenty-five American films annually for preservation and inclusion in the National Film Registry, a collection of American films, for which the Library of Congress accepts nominations each year.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] There also exists a National Recording Registry administered by the National Recording Preservation Board that serves a similar purpose for music and sound recordings.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library has made some of these available on the Internet for free streaming and additionally has provided brief essays on the films that have been added to the registry.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] By 2015, the librarian had named 650 films to the registry.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The films in the collection date from the earliest period to ones produced more than ten years ago; they are selected from nominations submitted to the board.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] During Billington's tenure, the library acquired General Lafayette's papers in 1996 from a castle at La Grange, France; they had previously been inaccessible.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It also acquired the only copy of the 1507 Waldseemüller world map ("America's birth certificate") in 2003; it is on permanent display in the library's Thomas Jefferson Building.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Using privately raised funds, the Library of Congress has created a reconstruction of Thomas Jefferson's original library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This has been on permanent display in the Jefferson building since 2008.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Under Billington, public spaces of the Jefferson Building were enlarged and technologically enhanced to serve as a national exhibition venue.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It has hosted more than 100 exhibitions.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Onsite access to the Library of Congress has been increased.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Billington gained an underground connection between the new U.S.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Capitol Visitors Center and the library in 2008 to increase both congressional usage and public tours of the library's Thomas Jefferson Building.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 2001, the library began a mass deacidification program, to extend the lifespan of almost 4 million volumes and 12 million manuscript sheets.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 2002, a new storage facility was completed at Fort Meade, Maryland, where a collection of storage modules have preserved and made accessible more than 4 million items from the library's analog collections.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Billington established the Library Collections Security Oversight Committee in 1992 to improve protection of the collections, and also the Library of Congress Congressional Caucus in 2008 to draw attention to the library's curators and collections.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He created the library's first Young Readers Center in the Jefferson Building in 2009, and the first large-scale summer intern (Junior Fellows) program for university students in 1991.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Under Billington, the library sponsored the Gateway to Knowledge in 2010 to 2011, a mobile exhibition to ninety sites, covering all states east of the Mississippi, in a specially designed eighteen-wheel truck.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This increased public access to library collections off-site, particularly for rural populations, and helped raise awareness of what was also available online.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Billington raised more than half a billion dollars of private support to supplement Congressional appropriations for library collections, programs, and digital outreach.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] These private funds helped the library to continue its growth and outreach in the face of a 30% decrease in staffing, caused mainly by legislative appropriations cutbacks.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He created the library's first development office for private fundraising in 1987.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1990, he established the James Madison Council, the library's first national private sector donor-support group.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1987, Billington also asked the Government Accountability Office (GAO) to conduct the first library-wide audit.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] He created the first Office of the Inspector General at the library to provide regular, independent reviews of library operations.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This precedent has resulted in regular annual financial audits at the library; it has received unmodified ("clean") opinions from 1995 onward.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In April 2010, the library announced plans to archive all public communication on Twitter, including all communication since Twitter's launch in March 2006.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] As of 2015, the Twitter archive remains unfinished.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Before retiring in 2015, after 28 years of service, Billington had come "under pressure" as librarian of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] When Billington announced his plans to retire in 2015, commentator George Weigel described the Library of Congress as "one of the last refuges in Washington of serious bipartisanship and calm, considered conversation", and "one of the world's greatest cultural centers".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Appointed in 2016 by President Barack Obama, Carla D.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Hayden was sworn in as the fourteenth librarian of Congress on September 14, 2016.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] She is the first professional librarian to hold the post since 1974, holding a Ph.D. in library science from the University of Chicago.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] She was the CEO of Enoch Pratt Free Library in Baltimore, Maryland, from 1993 until 2016, and president of the American Library Association (ALA) from 2003 to 2004.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] She also is the first woman and the first African American to hold the position.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] She continued the work of digitizing as much as possible of the collection and of expanding electronic access to the collection.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] She initiated programs to modernize the library, expand access from rural areas, and expanding the infrastructure and technological capacity of the library and assessment of her leadership of the library by the community reflects her expressed goals.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Association of Research Libraries noted Hayden's transformation of the library "into a more open, accessible, and celebrated U.S. institution, while reaffirming its role as the people’s library".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The American Library Association characterized Hayden as a "wise and faithful steward of the Library of Congress – the library she has called our 'national treasure'".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On January 6, 2021, at 1:11 pm EST, the Library's Madison Building and the Cannon House Office Building were the first buildings in the Capitol Complex to be ordered to evacuate as rioters breached security perimeters before storming the Capitol building.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Hayden clarified two days later that rioters did not breach any of the Library buildings or collections and all staff members were safely evacuated.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On February 14, 2023, Hayden announced that the Lilly Endowment gifted the library with $2.5 million as a five-year grant to "launch programs that foster greater understanding of religious cultures in Africa, Central Asia, and the Middle East".
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] On May 8, 2025, two days after Hayden had given testimony to the Senate Committee on Appropriations and the Committee on House Administration, via email and without any explanation, she was abruptly fired by President Trump.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] No replacement of Hayden has been nominated.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This has been interpreted as an attack on the separation of powers.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Perlmutter has sued to dispute the legality of the dismissal, as the register is appointed by, and responsible to, the librarian of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library developed a system of book classification called Library of Congress Classification (LCC), which is used by most U.S. research and university libraries.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library serves as a legal repository for copyright protection and copyright registration, and as the base for the United States Copyright Office.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Regardless of whether they register their copyright, all publishers are required to submit two complete copies of their published works to the library—this requirement is known as *mandatory deposit*.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Nearly 15,000 new items published in the U.S. arrive every business day at the library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Contrary to popular belief, however, the library does not retain all of these works in its permanent collection, although it does add an average of 12,000 items per day.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Rejected items are used in trades with other libraries around the world, distributed to federal agencies, or donated to schools, communities, and other organizations within the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The legal requirement of mandatory deposit was challenged in *Valancourt Books v.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Garland*, with the court finding that requiring a publisher to deposit copies of its books at the Library of Congress was a violation of the Takings Clause.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] As is true of many similar libraries, the Library of Congress retains copies of every publication in the English language that is deemed significant.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress states that its collection fills about 838 mi (1,349 km) of bookshelves and holds more than 167 million items with over 39 million books and other print materials.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] A 2000 study by information scientists Peter Lyman and Hal Varian suggested that the amount of uncompressed textual data represented by the 26 million books then in the collection was 10 terabytes.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library also administers the National Library Service for the Blind and Physically Handicapped, an audio book and braille library program provided to more than 766,000 Americans.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library's first digitization project, American Memory, was launched in 1990, and was initially planned to choose 160 million objects from its collection to make digitally available on LaserDiscs and CDs, which were distributed to schools and libraries.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] After realizing that this plan would be too expensive and inefficient, and with the rise of the Internet, the library decided to instead make digitized material available over the Internet.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This project was made official in the National Digital Library Program (NDLP), created in October 1994.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] By 1999, the NDLP had succeeded in digitizing over 5 million objects and had a budget of $12 million.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] As of 2022, the library's website contains 914 million unique digital objects, comprising over 21 petabytes of data.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] American Memory is a source for public domain image resources, as well as audio, video, and archived Web content.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Nearly all of the lists of holdings, the *catalogs* of the library, can be consulted directly on its website.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Librarians all over the world consult these catalogs, through the Web or through other media better suited to their needs, when they need to catalog for their collection a book published in the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] They use the Library of Congress Control Number to make sure of the exact identity of the book.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Digital images are also available at Snapshots of the Past, which provides archival prints.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library has a budget of $6–8 million each year for digitization, meaning that not all works can be digitized.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It makes determinations about what objects to prioritize based on what is especially important to Congress or potentially interesting for the public.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The 15 million digitized items represent less than 10% of the library's total 160-million-item collection.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library has chosen not to participate in other digital library projects such as Google Books and the Digital Public Library of America, although it has supported the Internet Archive project.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 1995, the Library of Congress established THOMAS, an online archive of the proceedings of the United States Congress, which included the full text of proposed legislation, bill summaries, and statuses, *Congressional Record* text, and an index of the *Congressional Record*.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 2005 and again in 2010, the THOMAS system received major updates.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] A migration to a more modernized Web system, Congress.gov, began in 2012, and the THOMAS system was retired in 2016.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Congress.gov is a joint project of the Library of Congress, the House, the Senate, and the Government Publishing Office.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress is physically housed in three buildings on Capitol Hill and a conservation center in rural Virginia.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library's Capitol Hill buildings are all connected by underground passageways, so that a library user need pass through security only once in a single visit.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library also has off-site storage facilities in Maryland for less commonly requested materials.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Thomas Jefferson Building is located between Independence Avenue and East Capitol Street on First Street SE.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Construction began in 1890 with granite supplied by New England Granite Works, owned by James G.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The building opened in 1897 as the main building of the library and is the oldest of the three buildings.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Known originally as the Library of Congress Building or Main Building, it took its present name on June 13, 1980.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The John Adams Building is located between Independence Avenue and East Capitol Street on 2nd Street SE, the block adjacent to the Jefferson Building.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The building was originally known as The Annex to the Main Building, which had run out of space.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It opened its doors to the public on January 3, 1939.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Copyright Office which moved to the Madison building in the 1970s.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The James Madison Memorial Building is located between First and Second Streets on Independence Avenue SE.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The building was constructed from 1971 to 1976, and serves as the official memorial to James Madison, a Founding Father and the fourth President of the United States.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Madison Building is also home to the United States Copyright Office and to the Mary Pickford Theater, the "motion picture and television reading room" of the Library of Congress.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The theater hosts regular free screenings of classic and contemporary movies and television shows.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Founded in 2007 and located in Culpeper, Virginia in Northern Virginia, the National Audio-Visual Conservation Center is the Library of Congress's newest building.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It was constructed out of a former Federal Reserve storage center and Cold War bunker.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The campus is designed to act as a single site to store all of the library's movie, television, and sound collections.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] It is named in honor of David Woodley Packard, whose Packard Humanities Institute oversaw the design and construction of the facility.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The centerpiece of the complex is a reproduction Art Deco movie theater that presents free movie screenings to the public on a semi-weekly basis.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress, through both the librarian of Congress and the register of copyrights, is responsible for authorizing exceptions to Section 1201 of Title 17 of the United States Code as part of the Digital Millennium Copyright Act.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] This process is done every three years, with the register receiving proposals from the public and acting as an advisor to the librarian, who issues a ruling on what is exempt.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] After three years have passed, the ruling is no longer valid and a new ruling on exemptions must be made.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The library is open for academic research to anyone with a Reader Identification Card.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] One may not remove library items from the reading rooms or the library buildings.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Most of the library's general collection of books and journals are in the closed stacks of the Jefferson and Adams Buildings; specialized collections of books and other materials are in closed stacks in all three main library buildings, or are stored off-site.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Access to the closed stacks is not permitted under any circumstances, except to authorized library staff, and occasionally, to dignitaries.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Only the reading room reference collections are on open shelves.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Since 1902, American libraries have been able to request books and other items through interlibrary loan from the Library of Congress if these items are not readily available elsewhere.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Through this system, the Library of Congress has served as a "library of last resort", according to Herbert Putnam, the librarian of Congress from 1899 to 1939.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress lends books to other libraries with the stipulation that they be used only inside the borrowing library.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In 2017, the Library of Congress began development on a reader's card for children under the age of sixteen.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] In addition to its library services, the Library of Congress is actively involved in various standard activities in areas related to bibliographical and search and retrieval standards.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Areas of work include MARC standards, Metadata Encoding and Transmission Standard (METS), Metadata Object Description Schema (MODS), Z39.50 and Search/Retrieve Web Service (SRW), and Search/Retrieve via URL (SRU).
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Law Library of Congress "seeks to further legal scholarship by providing opportunities for scholars and practitioners to conduct significant legal research.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] Individuals are invited to apply for projects which would further the multi-faceted mission of the law library in serving the U.S.
[src:american-memory/library-of-congress] The Library of Congress continues to host exhibitions, educational programs, and online resources, making its collections accessible to researchers and the public worldwide.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] The **National Digital Library Program** (**NDLP**) is a project by the United States Library of Congress to assemble a digital library of reproductions of primary source materials to support the study of the history and culture of the United States.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] The NDLP brought online 24 million books and documents from the Library of Congress and other research institutions.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] Begun in 1995 after a five-year pilot project, the program began digitizing selected collections of Library of Congress archival materials that chronicle the nation's history.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] In order to reproduce collections of books, pamphlets, motion pictures, manuscripts and sound recordings, the Library has created a range of digital entities: bitonal document images, grayscale and color pictorial images, digital video and audio, and searchable e-texts.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] To provide access to the reproductions, the project developed a range of descriptive elements: bibliographic records, finding aids, and introductory texts and programs, as well as indexing the full texts for certain types of content.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] The reproductions were produced with a variety of tools: image scanners, digital cameras, devices that digitize audio and video, and human labor for rekeying and encoding texts.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] In other cases, the lack of well established standards has led to the use of emerging formats, e.g., RealAudio (for audio), QuickTime (for moving images), and MrSID (for maps).
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] Technical information by types of material and by individual collections is also available on the site.
[src:american-memory/national-digital-library-program] The Library received funding from Congress and private sector donations, sponsoring a three-year competition to enable institutions like libraries to digitize their U.S. history collections.
